$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of biaryl
products (3a-o, 5a-d). In a drybox under argon atmosphere, to a flame
dried microwave vial equipped with a stir bar, was added the Fe(OAc)2
(0.025 mmol, 5 mol%), bathophenanthroline (0.05 mmol, 10 mol%), and
crushed dry KOt-Bu (1.0 mmol, 2 equiv). The vial was then sealed with a
septum. To a separate flame dried vial was added the aryl iodide (0.5
mmol, 1 equiv). The vial was subsequently sealed with a septum and purged
with argon. The iodide was diluted in the corresponding dried arene (12.5
mmol, 25 equiv) and added to the reaction vessel via syringe. The vial
and syringe were then rinsed with the arene (3 x 12.5 mmol, 25 equiv),
bringing the total amount of arene added to 100 equiv. The reaction was
stirred vigorously at room temperature for 20 min and then at 80°C for 20
h. Following cooling, 2 mL of CH2Cl2/hexanes (1:1) was added, and the
solution was filtered though a silica pad. The pad was then rinsed with
15 mL of CH2Cl2/hexanes (1:1). The combined solution was concentrated and
the crude mixture was purified via column chromatography to afford the
biphenyl products 3 / 5. 4-Methoxybiphenyl3, 4, 6, 7 [613-37-6] (3e) The
title compound 3e was prepared according to the general procedure
described above using 4-iodoanisole 1f with benzene, and purified by
column chromatography (100% hexanes) as a white solid (89.2 mg, 93%). Rf
= 0.14 (100% hexanes). The observed characterization data (1H) was
consistent with that previously reported in the literature. 1H NMR (300
MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.61 (t, J = 7.6 Hz, 4H), 7.48 (t, J = 7.6 Hz, 2H), 7.36
(t, J = 6.9 Hz, 1H), 7.03 (d, J = 8.7 Hz, 2H), 3.90 (s, 3H). 13C NMR (75
MHz, CDCl3) δ 159.6, 141.2, 134.1, 129.1, 128.5, 127.1, 127.0, 114.5,
55.7; LRMS Calcd for C13H12O M+: 184.09. Found: 184.

alternatively reaction carried out at room temperature for 60 hours gave
51% yield

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure of Cross-Coupling Reaction for
Separating Products. A 25 mL Schlenk tube was charged with
1,10-phenanthroline (45 mg, 0.25 mmol), KOt-Bu (225 mg, 2.0 mmol),
benzene or pyridine (5 mL), and aryl halides (0.5 mmol) in glovebox. Then
the tube was removed from the glovebox, and the resulting mixture was
stirred upon visible light irradiation (providing 400 mW cm-2 visible
light) for 24 h. The reaction was quenched with water in excess and the
residue was extracted with copious ethyl acetate. The combined organic
phase was concentrated under vacuum. The crude product was purified by
semipreparative HPLC (60% MeCN, 0.1% TFA) to give desired product.
Semipreparative HPLC was performed using an ODS column (ODS-A, 10 × 250
mm, 5 μm) at 5 mL/min. 1H NMR and 13C NMR were recorded on a BRUKER
BIOSPIN AVANCE III spectrometer using TMS as the internal standard.
4-Methoxybiphenyl (3b)[6] : 1H NMR (500 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 3.87 (s, 3H),
7.01 (d, J = 8.5 Hz, 2H), 7.26-7.35 (m, 1H), 7.44 (t, J = 7.0 Hz, 2H),
7.57 (t, J = 8.0 Hz, 4H). 13C NMR (125 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 55.4, 114.4,
126.9, 128.3, 128.9, 133.9, 141.1, 159.3.

nm)

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the direct arylation of
benzene with aryl iodides Aryl halides (1.0 mmol), PTSH (0.1 mmol, 10 mol
%), and KOt-Bu (3.0 mmol) were added to a Schlenk tube under a nitrogen
atmosphere at room temperature. Benzene (5 mL) was then added. The tube
was sealed and the mixture was stirred at 110°C. After cooling to room
temperature, the mixture was quenched with water (5 mL) and extracted
with ethyl acetate (3 × 10 mL). The combined organic phase was washed
with brine (10 mL), dried over anhydrous Na2SO4, filtered and
concentrated under vacuum. The crude product was purified by column
chromatography using petroleum ether /ethyl acetate as an eluent.
4-Methoxybiphenyl(3e)1 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.56 (t, J = 7.4 Hz,
4H), 7.43 (t, J = 7.4 Hz, 2H), 7.33 (d, J = 7.2 Hz, 1H), 7.00 (d, J = 8.7
Hz, 2H), 3.88 (d, J = 4.8 Hz, 3H). 13C NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3) δ 158.67,
140.35, 133.30, 128.25, 127.68, 126.26, 126.18, 113.73, 54.86.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DATUM 4-Methoxybiphenyl (48b): General procedure for synthesis of biphenyl
derivatives 36 and 48a-d: Aryl iodide 35b (52 mg, 0.2 mmol) was dissolved
in benzene (50 mL, 4 mmol). TTMSS (0.075 mL, 1.2 equiv.) and pyridine
(0.08 mL, 5 equiv.) were added and the resulting mixture was allowed to
stir at room temperature. Upon consumption of the aryl iodide (30 min to
3 hr), the reaction mixture was concentrated via rotoevaporation and the
resulting crude product was purified by flash chromatography on silica
gel eluting with hexanes/ethyl acetate (50:1) to provide the title
compound as a white solid (37 mg, 87 %). According to the general
procedure, using iodoanisole 47b (47 mg, 0.2 mmol) and eluting with
hexanes/ethyl acetate (30/1) yielded the title compound as a white solid
(33 mg, 90 %).

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for synthesis of biphenyl
derivatives 2a-f: Synthesis of biphenyl 4- carboxylic acid methyl ester
(2a): Aryl iodide 1a (52 mg, 0.2 mmol) was dissolved in benzene (50 mL, 4
mmol). TTMSS (0.075 mL, 1.2 equiv) and pyridine (0.08 mL, 5 equiv) were
added and the resulting mixture was allowed to stir at room temperature.
Upon consumption of the aryl iodide (30 min to 3 h), the reaction mixture
was concentrated via rotoevaporation and the resulting crude product was
purified by flash chromatography on silica gel eluting with hexanes/ethyl
acetate (50/1) to provide the title compound as a white solid (37 mg,
87%); CAS# 720-75-2. 1HNMR data consistent with Percec, V. et. al. J.
Org. Chem. 2004, 69, 3447. 4-Methoxybiphenyl (2c): Using iodoanisole 1c
(47 mg, 0.2 mmol) and eluting with hexanes/ethyl acetate (30/1) yielded
the title compound as a white solid (33 mg, 90%); CAS# 613-37-6. 1HNMR
data consistent with Percec, V. et. al. J. Org. Chem. 2004, 69, 3447.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM 3-Methyl-3-phenylbutanoic acid (16).20 3-Methyl-2-butenoic acid (5.10 g,
50.9 mmol) and AlCl3 (20.4 g, 153 mmol) were placed in a one-neck
round-bottomed flask. Benzene (50 mL) was added, which produced vigorous
bubbling. Upon completion of the bubbling, a capped condenser (i.e.,
closed system) was attached, and the reaction mixture was stirred and
placed in an oil bath at 65 °C. The pressure in the system was
occasionally released. The progress of the reaction was followed by the
loss of starting material by GC. If the reaction was not complete within
1 h, a small quantity of AlCl3 was added and stirring was continued. To
the solution was added diethyl ether, and the mixture was cooled to 0 °C.
Slowly concentrated HCl and some H2O were added until all the solid
dissolved and the pH was less than 2. The aqueous layer was extracted
with diethyl ether three times. The organic layer was concentrated to 150
mL and then was extracted with a saturated sodium hydrogen carbonate
solution six times. The combined aqueous layer was acidified with
concentrated HCl until the pH was less than 2. The acidic aqueous layer
was extracted with diethyl ether three times, and the accumulated organic
layer was dried with magnesium sulfate. The solution was filtered and the
diethyl ether was removed in vacuo, producing a white solid (8.51 g, 47.7
mmol) in 94% yield, which did not need further purification. 16:
3-Methyl-3-phenylbutanoic acid (16), yield 8.51 g, 47.7 mmol, 94% mp
55-56 °C; IR (KBr pellet) 3210-2100 (br), 1698, 1319, 696 cm-1; 1H NMR
(400 MHz, CDCl3) 1.47 (s, 6H), 2.65 (s, 2H), 7.21 (t, 2H, J = 7.2 Hz),
7.32 (t, 2H, J = 7.2 Hz), 7.38 (d, 2H, J = 7.2 Hz), 10.45 (bs, 1H); 13C
NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3) 28.7, 36.9, 47.9, 125.3, 126.0, 128.1, 147.9, 178.2;
HREIMS m/z 178.0995 (calcd for C11H14O2, 178.0993); anal. calcd for
C11H14O2, C 74.13%; H 7.92%; found, C 73.88%; H 7.99%.

$DATUM Journal of Natural Products (2003), 66(2), 183-199

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General method A, for preparation of
heterocyclic alcohols (2, 13-15): The N-heterocyclic trifluoromethyl
ketone (1 mmol) is dissolved in 2 mL CHCl3 and 2 mL C6H6; CF3SO3H (2 mL,
22 mmol) is added slowly with stirring. After a two hour reaction at
25°C, the mixture is poured on ice. More CHCl3 (ca. 30 mL) is then added
and the aqueous layer is made basic with 10 M NaOH. Separation of the
organic phase is followed by washings with water, and then twice with
saturated brine. The organic solution is dried with MgSO4, filtered, and
concentrated on a rotary evaporator. If necessary, the product may be
further purified by silica gel chromatography (hexanes:ether). Note: this
procedure has not been optimized and some substrates (i.e. 1) are found
to give better product yields with longer reaction times.
3-(1-(Trifluoromethyl)-2,3-dihydro-1,3-diphenyl-1H-inden-3-yl)pyridine
(21): Using general method A, compound 21 was isolated as yellow
crystals, Yield 94% (Rf 0.13, 2:1 hexanes:ethyl ether): MP 111-115°C
(C6H6). 1H NMR, 200 MHz, CDCl3, δ: 3.55-3.70 (m, 2H), 6.80-6.83 (m, 2H),
6.94-6.99 (m, 3H), 7.04-7.07 (m, 4H), 7.11-7.18 (m, 2H), 7.21-7.29 (m,
1H), 7.43-7.52 (m, 3H), 7.67-7.72 (m, 1H), 8.37-8.38 (m, 1H), 8.48-8.50
(m, 1H). 13C NMR, 50 MHz, CDCl3, δ: 52.2, 58.8, 60.5 (q, JC-F = 25 Hz),
122.9, 126.3, 126.8, 127.3, 127.6 (q, JC-F = 280 Hz), 127.6, 127.7,
127.8, 128.4, 128.5, 129.0, 135.7, 136.8, 139.8, 142.9, 143.4, 146.7,
149.1, 150.0. EI-MS: 415 (M+), 338, 337, 268. HRMS clacd for C27H2ONF3
415.15478, found 415.15521.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM (E)-1-(2-Bromovinyl)-4-methylbenzene (103): General Method (Sythesis of
characterization of vinyl bromides): Dibromomethane (281 microL, 4 mmol)
was added dropwise to a solution of NaHMDS (550 mg, 3.0 mmol) in THF (2
mL) and ether (2 mL) at -78 degC (dry ice/acetone bath) in the dark.
After 20 min, a solution of the benzyl bromide substrate (1.0 mmol) in
THF (1 mL) was added dropwise. The reaction mixture was maintained at -78
degC for at least 3 hr then continued stirred at -78 degC allowing to
warm to rt slowly over 16 hr. Ether (50 mL) was added then the mixture
was filtered through a plug of celite/silica (approximately 3 cm celite
over 3 cm silica) and the solvent removed under reduced pressure. The
residue was purified by flash chromatography to provide the vinyl
bromide. Prepared according to the general procedure for vinyl bromides
starting from 4-methylbenzyl bromide (186 mg, 1.0 mmol). Purification by
flash chromatography (hexanes, 100 %) afforded vinyl bromide 103 as a
white solid (179 mg, 91 %, > 99:1 E:Z). Rf = 0.59 (hexanes, 100 %).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Mousseau, James J.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Arylation Procedure . To a microwave
vial equipped with a stir bar was added Pd(OAc)2 (5.4 mg, 5 mol %), and
Ag2CO3 (71 mg, 0.51 equiv). The aryl halide was weighed into a separate
vial (0.5 mmol, 1 equiv). The halide was dissolved/mixed in ¼ the amount
of arene coupling partner and added to the reaction vessel via syringe.
The vial ws then rinsed 3x ¼ the volume of the arene to reach the total
reaction volume. The microwave vial was sealed with Teflon cap and
stirred at 125 °C for 16 h. Upon cooling, the reaction was filtered
through a silica plug (1:1 Et2O:hexanes). The combined solution was
concentrated and the crude mixture was purified via column chromatography
to afford the biphenyl products. Methyl 4-nitrobiphenyl-2-carboxylate
(4b) The title compound 4b was prepared according to the general
procedure described above using methyl 2-bromo-5-nitrobenzoate 3b with
benzene (100 equiv), and purified by column chromatography (30% ether in
hexanes) as a beige solid (122.0 mg, 94%). Rf = 0.38 (30% ether in
hexanes). The observed characterization data (1H) was consistent with
that previously reported in the literature.11 Rf = 0.38 (30% ether in
hexanes). 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ 8.69 (d, J = 2.4 Hz, 1H), 8.37 (dd, J
= 8.5, 2.5 Hz 1H), 7.58 (d, J = 8.5 Hz, 1H), 7.48-7.45 (m, 3H), 7.35-7.32
(m, 2H), 3.73 (s, 3H). LRMS Calcd for C14H11NO4 M+: 257.24. Found: 257.

$DATUM Preparation of 2-(2-bromophenyl)-2-phenylpropane The solution of
2-(2-bromphenyl)-2-chloropropane (3) (5 g; 21 mmol) in 5 ml of dry
benzene was gradually added during 2 h into the stirred and cooled
(5-8°C) mixture of anhydrous AlCl3 (0.29 g; 2.1 mmol) in 15 ml of dry
benzene. The reaction mixture was stirred for an additional hour and then
poured onto crushed ice, and organic product was extracted into benzene.
Benzene extract was washed with saturated aqueous solution of sodium
bicarbonate and dried over anhydrous sodium sulfate. Solution was
filtered off, and solvent was evaporated under reduced pressure to give
the oily residue of pure product (4), 5.4 g (94%).
2-(2-bromophenyl)-2-phenylpropane (4), yield (5.4 g, 94%). 1H-NMR
spectrum (CDCl3): 1.76 (6H, s, CH3), 7.08-7.67 (9H, m, Har).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 2.1.3. Synthesis of 2-benzylbenzonitriles 1 by
the Friedel–Crafts reaction: A typical procedure for synthesis of
2-benzyl-1-naphthonitrile 1n To a flask charged with AlCl3 (0.989 g, 7.42
mmol) in dry benzene (9.3 mL) was added 2-(bromomethyl)-1-naphthonitrile
10n (0.911 g, 3.70 mmol) in an ice bath. The reaction mixture was warmed
to room temperature and then heated to reflux for 45 min. When all the
starting materials were consumed, as checked by TLC, the reaction mixture
was cooled to room temperature, poured into ice and then acidified with 1
N HCl. The organic materials were extracted with CH2Cl2. The combined
organic extracts were washed with water and then with brine and dried
over anhydrous MgSO4. The solvents were removed in vacuo and the
resulting crude material was subjected to flash column chromatography
(hexane : EtOAc = 90 : 10). 2-benzyl-1-naphthonitrile 1n (0.711 g, 2.92
mmol) in 79% yield. 2-benzyl-6-chlorobenzonitrile (1j) 94% yield from
10j; Yellow solid. mp. 36.0-37.0 °C; IR (NaCl) 3065, 2232, 1589, 1564,
1454, 1439, 669 cm-1; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 4.21 (2H, s), 7.16 (1H,
d, J = 8.0 Hz), 7.22-7.27 (3H, m), 7.31 (2H, d, J = 7.2 Hz), 7.35 (1H, d,
J = 8.4 Hz), 7.41 (1H, dd, J = 7.6, 8.0 Hz); 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3) δ
40.5, 113.6, 115.2, 126.9, 127.6, 128.0, 128.8, 129.0, 133.3, 137.4,
138.0, 147.4; ESIHRMS: Found: m/z 228.0576. Calcd for C14H11NCl: (M+H)+
228.0580.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure of Cross-Coupling Reaction for
Separating Products. A 25 mL Schlenk tube was charged with
1,10-phenanthroline (45 mg, 0.25 mmol), KOt-Bu (225 mg, 2.0 mmol),
benzene or pyridine (5 mL), and aryl halides (0.5 mmol) in glovebox. Then
the tube was removed from the glovebox, and the resulting mixture was
stirred upon visible light irradiation (providing 400 mW cm-2 visible
light) for 24 h. The reaction was quenched with water in excess and the
residue was extracted with copious ethyl acetate. The combined organic
phase was concentrated under vacuum. The crude product was purified by
semipreparative HPLC (60% MeCN, 0.1% TFA) to give desired product.
Semipreparative HPLC was performed using an ODS column (ODS-A, 10 × 250
mm, 5 μm) at 5 mL/min. 1H NMR and 13C NMR were recorded on a BRUKER
BIOSPIN AVANCE III spectrometer using TMS as the internal standard.
4-Methoxybiphenyl (3b)[6] : 1H NMR (500 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 3.87 (s, 3H),
7.01 (d, J = 8.5 Hz, 2H), 7.26-7.35 (m, 1H), 7.44 (t, J = 7.0 Hz, 2H),
7.57 (t, J = 8.0 Hz, 4H). 13C NMR (125 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 55.4, 114.4,
126.9, 128.3, 128.9, 133.9, 141.1, 159.3.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM photochemical, alternative preparation shown, Schlenk flask used,
glovebox used, alternative reaction conditions shown, UV light used (320
nm)

$DATUM Synthesis of Ir(NNC)Cl(C6H5)Py (2-Py): Complex 1-Cl (52mg, 8.28x10-2
mmol) was heated at 160°C in benzene (80ml) in a thick-walled glass
vacuum bulb equipped with a PTFE valve for 1h. The solvent was removed
under vacuum, and then redissolved in pyridine (10ml). Solvent was
removed and the residue was purified by alumina prep TLC using CH2Cl2.
Pure 2-Py was precipitated from CH2Cl2/pentane. Yield 55.7mg (92.5%).
Ir(NNC)Cl(C6H5)Py (2-Py), yield 55.7mg (92.5%). ESI-MS: 750.2 (M + Na)+
728.2 (M + H)+. Elemental analysis for 2-Py: -Found C 56.97, H 4.86, Cl
4.87, N 5.74, Calc. C 57.79; H 5.13; Cl 4.87; N 5.78. 1H NMR (CDCl3)
9.30(d, 1H, 3J = 5.8, H-1), 8.32(dd, 2H, o-Py), 8.07(dd, 1H, 3J = 7.6 4J=
1.2, H-15), 7.87(d, 1H, 4J= 1.7, H-4), 7.72(d, 1H, 3J = 1.8, H-7),

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General Procedure for the Preparation of Condensed Products 10-19. A 0.2
g portion of the acetyl-substituted heteroarene was dissolved in 1.0 mL
of C6H6, and to this solution was added 5.0 mL of triflic acid. This
mixture was stirred at room temperature (6 was reacted at 50 °C) for
4-12h and then poured over several grams of ice. The resulting solution
was made basic with concentrated NaOH and extractedwith CHCl3. The
organic phase was washed with H2O and brine and then dried with MgSO4.
Removal of the solvent under reduced pressure then provided the product.
The product (s) was then purified by recrystallization or column
chromatography. 2-(1,1-Diphenylethyl)pyridine, yield 93%. mp 51-54 °C
(CHCl3, mp 54-56 °C); 1H NMR δ 2.27 (s, 3H), 7.01 (d, J = 8.1 Hz, 1H),
7.11-7.15 (m, 4H), 7.20-7.32 (m, 7H), 7.55 (dt, J = 1.8, 7.5, 1H), 8.65
(m, 1H); 13C NMR δ 29.4, 55.1, 121.0, 123.6, 126.9, 128.0, 128.6, 135.8,
148.3, 148.9, 167.1; EI MS 259 (M+); HRMS m/z calcd for C19H17N 259.1361,
found 259.1369.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Klumpp, Douglas A.; Garza, Manuel; Sanchez, Gregorio V. Jr.; Lau, Siufu;
de Leon, Sarah

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for Oxidative Coupling of
Benzene (1a) with Ethyl Acrylate (2a). A solution of Pd(OAc)2 (0.1 mmol),
H4PMo11V1O40•nH2O (HPMo11V1, n = 30) (46.7 mg, ca. 0.02 mmol), NaOAc
(0.08 mmol), acetylacetone (0.1 mmol), benzene (1a) (30 mmol), and ethyl
acrylate (2a) (1.5 mmol) in propionic acid (5 mL) was placed in a
round-bottom flask (30 mL) equipped with a balloon filled with O2, and
the mixture was allowed to react under stirring at 90 °C for 2.5 h. 3ae,
yield 93% 1H NMR (270 MHz, CDCl3) δ 1.88 (s, 3H), 0.98 (s, 1H), 7.19-7.42
(m, 10H); 13C NMR (67.5 MHz, CDCl3) δ 30.3, 127.3, 127.8, 128.3, 128.6,
129.3, 138.8, 140.6, 153.8, 200.0.

$DATUM Preparation Example II-10: Preparation of Compound B-10 The compound
B-10-1 (6.6 g, 15.9 mmol) and benzene (100mL) were mixed, CF3SO3H (1.6mL,
18.4 mmol) was added thereto, and the mixture was refluxed at 80°C for 6
hours. Using an ice-bath, the reaction solution was cooled to 0°C and a
saturated aqueous solution of NaHCO3 was added thereto. The layer was
separated using water and ethylacetate, and the organic layer was
separated and dried over magnesium anhydride. Then, the organic layer was
subjected to reduced pressure in vacuum, and recrystallized with
THF/Hexane to prepare a compound B-10 (7.0 g, yield 93%). MS : [M]+ = 476

$DATUM The imidazole substrate (0.1 g) is dissolved in benzene (or other arene;
1.0 mL) and CF3SO3H(1-2 mL) is added. The reaction is stirred at least 2
h, and then the mixture is poured over several grams of ice. The mixture
is made basic (pH paper) with the slow addition of 10 M NaOH. The
resulting solution is extracted twice with CHCl3, and the combined
organic extracts are further washed with water (once) and then brine
(twice). If purification is necessary, the product mixture is subjected
to column chromatography (silica gel; hexane/ ether).
2-Benzhydryl-1-methyl-1H-imidazole (6). Using general procedure A,
compound 1 is reacted with C6H6 and CF3SO3H. Product 6 is isolated. 1H
NMR (CDCl3): δ 3.47 (s, 3H), 5.51 (s, 1H), 6.87 (s, 1H), 7.05 (s, 1H),
7.20-7.35 (m, 10H). 13C NMR (CDCl3): δ 32.9, 49.5, 121.0, 126.9, 127.6,
128.6, 128.9, 141.0, 148.7. Low resolution MS (EI): 248 (M+), 247, 165.
High resolution MS (EI), C17H16N2 calcd: 248.13135, found 248.13070.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Reaction of AF4-Acetamide 6 with Anthracene
under Cadogan Conditions. A 50-mL three-necked round-bottom flask was
charged with AF4-acetamide 6 (0.205 g, 0.500 mmol), 5 mL of n-butyl
ether, and anthracene (0.18 g, 1.00 mmol, 2.00 equiv). This mixture was
heated to 110 °C and PCBN (0.16 g, 0.85mmol) in 10 mL of n-butyl ether
was added over a period of 30 min. The reaction mixture was maintained at
this temperature overnight. Then the mixture was cooled and the solvent
evaporated under vacuum. The residue was purified on a silica gel column,
eluting with hexanes/ethyl acetate (100:1) to give the white crystalline
Diels-Alder, 9,10-adduct 5 in yields that were consistently about 95%,
with less than 3% of the 1,4 adduct being detected. 1H, 13C, and 19F NMR
spectra of 5 were consistent with those reported previously.15 When the
reaction was carried out in refluxing benzene with no other substrate,
the benzene adduct 7 was obtained in 90% yield. 1H, 13C, and 19F NMR
spectra of 7 and 8 were consistent with those reported previously.15
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM Diels-Alder reaction, Cadogan conditions
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Remarkable Efficiency of the Aryne Chemistry of
(Dehydro)octafluoro[2.2]paracyclophane When Using the Cadogan Method
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Dolbier, William R. Jr.; Zhai, Yi-An; Wheelus, Will; Battiste, Merle A.;
Ghiviriga, Ion; Bartberger, Michael D.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Journal of Organic Chemistry (2007), 72(2), 550-558

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of
compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in
arene (3.0 mL) was added boron trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The
mixture was cooled to 0°C and then homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl
compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by drop over 10 min. The temperature was
slowly brought to rt in 1h. The reaction mixture was stirred at rt for
specified time. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC using
ethyl acetate and hexane as eluents. After completion of the reaction,
the product was extracted with ethyl acetate, washed with brine and
water. The organic layer was dried (Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the
crude product, which was purified by short column chromatography over
silica gel to give the title compounds.
4-Phenyl-2-(4-trifluoromethyl-phenyl)-tetrahydropyran (8b): Liquid, 93%
yield 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.70 (q, J = 12.0 Hz, 1 H), 1.82-1.94
(m, 2 H), 2.07 (dquint, J = 13.6 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 2.97 (tt, J = 12.0 and
4.4 Hz, 1 H), 3.76 (dt, J = 11.6 and 4.0 Hz, 1 H), 4.30 (ddd, J = 11.6,
4.0 and 1.6 Hz, 1 H), 4.53 (dd, J = 11.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 7.19-7.33 (m,
5 H), 7.48 (d, J = 8.4, 2 H), 7.58 (d, J = 8.4, 2 H). 13C NMR (100 MHz,
CDCl3): δ 33.3, 41.7, 42.1, 68.6, 79.1, 124.4 (q, J = 270.7 Hz), 125.2,
126.1, 126.6, 126.8, 128.7, 129.5 (q, J = 32.1 Hz), 145.3, 147.1. 19F NMR
(376 MHz, CDCl3/C6F6): δ 99.36 (s, 3F).IR: 3064, 3030, 2919, 2848, 1622,
1416, 1326, 1164, 1127, 1091, 1067, 838, 760, 700 cm-1 . Anal. Calcd for
C18H17F3O: C, 70.58; H, 5.59. Found: C, 70.64; H, 5.55.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM stereoselective, Friedel-Crafts reaction (Prins), ring-closing metathesis
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Stereoselective One-Pot, Three-Component Synthesis of
4-Aryltetrahydropyran via Prins-Friedel-Crafts Reaction

$DATUM rac-(ebthi)Zr(NHCMe3)(phenyl) (1m): A solution of complex 1a (0.094 g,
0.21 mmol) in benzene (5.0 mL) was heated in a glass vessel equipped with
a vacuum stopcock under an atmosphere of N2 for 24 h at 75 °C. The
volatile materials were removed under vacuum. The resulting yellow oil
was subsequently dissolved in diethyl ether (4 mL), and the ether was
then removed under vacuum to yield 1m as a colorless foam (0.100 g, 93%,
greater than95% pure by 1H NMR spectroscopy (Figure S-11)). The foam was
washed with n-pentane (1 mL) and the remaining powder was dried under
reduced pressure, leaving 1m as an analytically pure, colorless solid. 1H
NMR (500 MHz) δ 7.79 (d, J = 6.7 Hz, 2H, ArHo), 7.26 (dd, J = 7.3, J =
6.7 Hz, 2H, ArHm), 7.15 (t, J = 7.3 Hz, 1H, ArHp), 6.45 (d, J = 2.8 Hz,
1H, CpH), 6.06 (d, J = 3.1 Hz, 1H, CpH), 5.50 (d, J = 2.9 Hz, 1H, CpH),
5.31 (d, J = 2.9 Hz, 1H, CpH), 4.76 (s, 1H, NH), 2.6-2.5 (m, 4H), 2.4-2.2
(m, 7H), 2.2-2.1 (m, 1H), 1.8-1.6 (m, 2H), 1.5-1.4 (m, 2H), 1.33 (s, 9H,
CMe3), 1.2-1.1 (m, 2H), 1.1-0.9 (m, 2H) ppm. 13C{1H} NMR (125 MHz) δ
182.33 (ZrC), 141.88 (Ar), 126.73 (ebthiq), 126.31 (Ar), 126.26 (ebthiq),
125.56 (ebthiq), 124.76 (Ar), 123.52 (ebthiq), 122.35 (ebthiq), 118.93
(ebthiq), 112.73 (ebthit), 107.09 (ebthit), 105.08 (ebthit), 102.07
(ebthit), 57.38 (HNCMe3), 35.06 (HNCMe3), 27.72 (CH2), 27.12 (CH2), 24.66
(CH2), 24.01 (CH2), 23.54 (CH2), 23.31 (CH2), 23.26 (CH2), 23.08 (CH2),

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure for the Arylation of Alkynes:
Approximately 0.2 g of alkyne (ca. 1 mmol) is dissolved in 1 mL C6H6 and
4 mL of triflic acid is added (NOTE: if the amino-alkyne is used as a HCl
or HBr salt, the reaction vessel should be equipped with a vent to
release HCl or HBr gas). The mixture is stirred for 6 hrs and poured over
about 15 g of ice. The resulting mixture is made basic with 50% NaOH and
extracted twice with CHCl3. The organic extracts are washed with water,
then brine, and dried over MgSO4. Concentration with reduced pressure
then gives the products; if necessary, column chromatography is done over
silica. Product 33 1H NMR, 300 MHz, CDCl3, δ: 1.60-1.82 (m, 2H), 1.86 (s,
3H), 2.00-2.12 (m, 1H), 2.16-2.31(m, 1H), 2.52-2.62 (m, 1H), 2.76-2.99
(m, 2H), 3.34- 3.46 (m, 1H), 3.72-3.84 (m, 1 H), 4.06-4.20 (m, 1H), 6.94
(d, J = 7.5 Hz, 1H), 7.04 (d, J = 7.8 Hz, 1H), 7.15-7.34 (m, 6H). 13C
NMR, 125 MHz, CDCl3, δ: 21.1, 27.7, 28.7, 29.4, 42.8, 52.6, 53.3, 125.6,
127.2, 127.4, 128.0, 128.2, 128.5, 129.0, 137.0, 141.5, 144.9; EI-MS,
m/z: 263 (M+), 262, 219,185; HRMS, calcd for C19H21N: 263.167400; found:
263.167899; MP: 244-246°C (benzene)

vacuum, the residue was redissolved in CH2Cl2, and reprecipitated with
pentane. Yield 94.7mg (91.8%). [Ir(NNC)Cl(C6H5)]2 [2]2 , yield 94.7mg
(91.8%). Elemental analysis: Calculated: C 55.58; H 4.98; N 4.32; Cl 5.47

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for Preparation of 2a-e and
4a-e Benzylsulfonyl acetic acids were prepared according to the procedure
reported in the literature.[3.6] To a suspension of 4-chloro
benzylsulfonyl acetic acid (1.0 g, 4.1 mmol) in benzene (30mL) was added
P2O5 (4.0 g) and the mixture was refluxed on oil bath for 5-8 h. The
reaction mixture was then cooled to room temperature and 25 mL of
dichloromethane was added to the flask and the contents were filtered
through a Buchner funnel. The remaining viscous solid was washed twice
(50 mL) with DCM and filtered. The combined filtrates were concentrated
under reduced pressure and the residue was purified by column
chromatography (SiO2) with chloroform to yield 2 or 4.
Phenacyl-4-chlorohenzyl sulfone (2b). Yield 92%. 1H NMR (400 MHz): δ =
4.56 (s, 2H), 4.69 (s, 2H), 7.56 (d, 2H), 7.64-7.71 (m, 4H), 7.83 (s,
1H), 8.14 (d, 2H). 13C NMR (100 MHz): δ = 57.27, 59.37, 126.62, 129.48,
129.49, 129.55, 129.74, 132.86, 135.19, 135.98, 136.12, 164.15, 189.96.
Anal. Ca1cd. for C15H13SO3Cl: C, 58.35; H, 4.24. Found: C, 58.22; H,
3.98. M·p· (°C) 150-154.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Solvent dependent dehydrating condensation of benzylsulfonyl acetic acids

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of
compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in
arene (3.0 mL) was added boron trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The
mixture was cooled to 0°C and then homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl
compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by drop over 10 min. The temperature was
slowly brought to rt in 1h. The reaction mixture was stirred at rt for
specified time. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC using
ethyl acetate and hexane as eluents. After completion of the reaction,
the product was extracted with ethyl acetate, washed with brine and
water. The organic layer was dried (Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the
crude product, which was purified by short column chromatography over
silica gel to give the title compounds.
4-Phenyl-2,6-di(4-nitrophenyl)-tetrahydropyran (21b): Solid, 92% yield
M.P.: 224-225°C; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.78 (q, J = 12.8 Hz, 2 H),
2.23-2.26 (m, 2 H), 3.25 (tt, J = 12.4, and 3.6 Hz, 1 H), 4.89 (dd, J =
1.2 and 1.6 Hz, 2 H), 7.24-7.35 (m, 5 H), 7.65 (d, J = 8.8 Hz, 4 H), 8.24
(d, J = 8.8 Hz, 4 H); 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ 41.0, 42.3, 79.2,
123.9, 126.6, 126.9, 127.2, 129.0, 144.0, 147.5, 149.6; IR: 3085, 2915,
2846, 1600, 1512, 1344, 1103, 1091, 850 cm-1 . Anal. Calcd for
C23H20N2O5: C, 68.31; H, 4.98; N, 6.93. Found: C, 68.39; H, 5.10; N,
6.87.

$DATUM 1-Methyl-4-(2-methyl-3,3-diphenylpropyl)piperazine (28). Amine 27 (0.102
g, 0.43 mmol) was suspended in 1 mL of anhydrous benzene, to which was
added CF3SO3H (1.0 mL, 1.9 mmol). The mixture was stirred at 25°C for 4-6
h, after which the solution was poured over several grams of ice.
Chloroform (30 mL) was poured into the mixture, and the aqueous phase was
made basic (pH paper) by slow addition of 10 M NaOH. Extraction and
separation of the organic phase was followed by a second chloroform
extraction (30 mL) of the aqueous phase. The combined chloroform extracts
were washed with H2O and then brine (twice). Following a drying step
(Na2SO4), filtration, removal of solvent, and silica gel chromatography
(ether/hexanes). Compound 28 was isolated (0.123 g, 0.0004 mmol) as a
light-brown solid. Mp: 141-142°C. 1H NMR (CDCl3, 500 MHz) δ: 0.95 (d, J =
6.5 Hz, 3H), 2.13 (dd, J = 3.1, 10.8 Hz, 1H), 2.28 (dd, J = 4.4, 12.4 Hz,
1H), 2.40-2.45 (m, 3H), 2.61-2.67 (m, 8H), 3.70 (d, J = 9.6 Hz, 1H),
7.18-7.33 (m, 9H). 13C NMR (CDCl3, 125 MHz) δ: 17.4, 34.3, 45.4, 52.6,
54.9, 56.8, 63.2, 126.1, 126.1, 128.0, 128.4, 128.5, 143.9, 144.2.
Low-resolution MS (EI) m/z: 308 (M+), 252, 193, 167, 165, 113, 70. HRMS
(EI) m/z: calcd for C21H28N2, 308.22525, found 308.22471.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Synthetic Procedure (Products 14-26).
Approximately 0.2 g of the olefin is suspended in 2 mL of benzene and 3
mL of TfOH is added. After being stirred for at least 3 h, the mixture is
poured over ice, and it is made basic with concentrated NaOH. The mixture
is then extracted with CHCl3 and the organic phase is washed with brine,
dried with MgSO4, and concentrated under vacuum.
4-Methyl-5-(1-phenylethyl)thiazole (26), yield 92% 1H NMR (CDCl3, 300
MHz) δ 1.67 (d, J = 6.9 Hz, 3H), 2.35 (s, 3H), 4.38 (q, J = 6.9 Hz, 1H),
7.19-7.33 (m, 5H), 8.57 (s, 1H) ppm. 13C NMR (CDCl3, 125 MHz) δ 15.5,
24.2, 37.8, 126.8, 127.2, 128.9, 129.5, 145.1, 149.4, 149.5 ppm. MS m/z
(EI) 203 (M+), 188. HRMS calcd for C12H13NS 203.076871, found 203.077637.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM regioselective, Friedel-Crafts alkylation
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM 4-Phenyltetrahydro-2H-pyran (32). A solution of aluminum chloride (2.67
g, 20.0 mmol) in anhydrous benzene (50 mL) was cooled to 0°C in an
ice/water bath under a nitrogen atmosphere and treated dropwise with a
solution of 4-chlorotetrahydro-2H-pyran (31) (2.11g, 17.5 mmol) in
anhydrous benzene (5 mL). Caution: gas evolution and exothermic reaction!
When the addition was complete, the cooling bath was removed and the
reaction stirred at room temperature for 1 h. After this time, the
reaction was poured into a mixture of ice/water (200 mL) and extracted
with diethyl ether (200 mL). The organic phase was dried over sodium
sulfate and filtered and the filtrate concentrated under reduced
pressure. 4-phenyltetrahydro-2H-pyran (2.62 g, 92%) as a yellow solid
which was used in the next step without purification. 1H NMR (400 MHz,
DMSO-d6 ) δ 7.29-7.17 (m, 5H), 3.96-3.92 (m, 2H), 3.46-3.40 (m, 2H),
2.84-2.72 (m, 1H), 1.69-1.64 (m, 4H).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM Friedel-Crafts reaction, exothermic in stage 1

$DATUM Preparation of [Rh2(O2CCF3)4(DM-DCNQI)]∞.(C6H6) (1). Rh2(O2CCF3)4 (66 mg,
0.1 mmol) was dissolved in 20 mL of dichloromethane/ benzene (1:1 v/v).
This solution was placed in a narrow Schlenk tube and layered with a
benzene solution of DM-DCNQI (18 mg, 0.1 mmol). After standing
undisturbed for 1 week, the solution yielded a crop of reddish-brown
crystals. Yield, 92%. IR (cm-1) (Nujol mull): ν(CξN), 2216; ν(C-O), 1537;
δ (C-H) (phenyl), 844.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure for the CF3SO3H-Catalyzed Reactions.
In a 50mL glass pressure tube (with Teflon screw cap), ~100 mg of the
pyrazine derivative is dissolved in 2mL benzene, and 5mL triflic acid is
then slowly added. The sealed tube is then heated to 80°C. After 4h, tube
is cooled and the product mixture is poured onto ice. The resulting
solution is neutralized by 10.0 M NaOH solution, and extracted twice with
CHCl3. The organic phase is washed with brine and then dried over
anhydrous Na2SO4. After concentration, the products are then purified by
flash column chromatography (etehr:hexane).
2-(1-Methyl-2-phenyl-ethyl)-pyrazine (2b). Clear, brown oil; 1H NMR 500
MHz, CDCl3, δ: 1.34 (d, 3H, J = 6.9 Hz), 2.91 (dd, 1H, J = 7.5 Hz, 13.4
Hz), 3.08 (dd, 1H, J = 7.5Hz, 13.4Hz), 3.19-3.26 (m, 1H), 7.05 (d, 2H, J
= 7.0Hz), 7.15-7.16 (m, 1H), 7.20-7.23 (m, 2H), 8.28 (s, 1H), 8.35 (d,
1H, J = 2.3Hz), 8.51 (s, 1H). 13C NMR 125 MHz, CDCl3, δ: 19.9, 41.4,
42.9, 126.1, 128.3, 129.0, 139.9, 142.4, 144.1, 160.7. Low resolution
mass spectrum (EI) m/z: 198 (M+), 183, 91. HRMS: calcd for C13H14N2:
198.1157, measured 198.1163

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Typical experimental procedure for preparative scale. 2 (Table 3, entry
1). Ethyl cinnamate (246 mg, 1.50 mmol, 1.0 equiv.), benzene (1.5 mL,
11.2 equiv.), Pd(OAc)2 (16.8 mg, 0.05 equiv.), 3,5-dichloropyridine (11.1
mg, 0.05 equiv.), tert-butyl peroxybenzoate (285 µL, 1.0 equiv.), and
acetic acid (7.0 mL) were combined in a 20 mL scintillation vial equipped
with a magnetic stir bar. The vial was sealed with a Teflon-lined cap.
The reaction was stirred at 100°C for 6 h. The resulting reaction mixture
was diluted with ethyl acetate (15 mL) and quenched with a 10% aqueous
Na2SO3 solution (20 mL). The organic layer was separated and washed with
10% aqueous Na2SO3 solution (2 x 20 mL), saturated aqueous NaHCO3
solution (3 x 20 mL), and brine (1 x 20 mL). The organic layer was dried
over MgSO4, filtered, and concentrated under reduced pressure. The
product was purified by column chromatography on silica gel. Some
products were further purified by HPLC (6 mL/min, Waters SunFire Prep
Silica 5 µm). Ethyl 3,3-diphenylacrylate (Table 3, Entry 1) The title
compound was prepared via the standard procedure using ethyl cinnamate
(246 mg, 1.50 mmol, 1.0 equiv.), benzene (1.5 mL, 11.2 equiv.), Pd(OAc)2
(16.8 mg, 0.05 equiv.), 3,5-dichloropyridine (11.1 mg, 0.05 equiv.),
tert-butyl peroxybenzoate (285 µL, 1.0 equiv.), and acetic acid (7.0 mL).
The product was obtained as a clear oil (286 mg, 76% yield). 1H and 13C
NMR spectral data of the isolated material matched the spectral data
reported in the literature for this compound.3
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

Fujiwara-Moritani reaction, optimized on ligand, sealed vial used

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of
compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in
arene (3.0 mL) was added boron trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The
mixture was cooled to 0°C and then homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl
compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by drop over 10 min. The temperature was
slowly brought to rt in 1h. The reaction mixture was stirred at rt for
specified time. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC using
ethyl acetate and hexane as eluents. After completion of the reaction,
the product was extracted with ethyl acetate, washed with brine and
water. The organic layer was dried (Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the
crude product, which was purified by short column chromatography over
silica gel to give the title compounds.
2-(3-Chloro-phenyl)-4-phenyl-tetrahydropyran (6b): Liquid, 92% yield 1H
NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.70 (q, J = 12.4 Hz, 1 H), 1.81-1.93 (m, 2 H),
2.06 (dquint, J = 13.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 2.95 (tt, J = 12.0 and 4.0 Hz, 1
H), 3.75 (dt, J = 11.6 and 3.6 Hz, 1 H), 4.28 (ddd, J = 12.0, 4.0 and 2.0
Hz, 1 H), 4.46 (dd, J = 11.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 7.19-7.33 (m, 8 H), 7.40
(s, 1 H). 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ 33.1, 41.4, 41.8, 68.4, 78.8,
123.8, 125.9, 126.4, 126.7, 127.3, 128.5, 129.5, 134.1, 145.0, 145.1. IR:
3062, 3028, 2917, 2939, 2845, 1600, 1575, 1429, 1355, 1130, 1086, 863,
784, 758, 699 cm -1 . Anal. Calcd for C17H17ClO: C, 74.86; H, 6.28.
Found: C, 74.91; H, 6.17.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DATUM Stereoselective One-Pot, Three-Component Synthesis of
4-Aryltetrahydropyran via Prins-Friedel-Crafts Reaction

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure A for the arylation of
anilides with benzene: An oven-dried Schlenk tube equipped with a stir
bar and a teflon stopper was cooled to room temperature under vacuum and
backfilled with O2. With the tube open to the air, the anilide (1.00
mmol) and Pd(OAc)2 (11.3-22.6 mg, 5-10 mol%) were added. The tube was
evacuated and backfilled with O2, followed by addition of benzene (1 mL,
~11 equiv), TFA (370 μL, 5.00 equiv), and DMSO (7-14 μL, 10-20 mol%) by
syringe under a positive O2 pressure with the tube open to the air. The
tube was sealed and lowered into a preheated oil bath at 55-100 °C and
stirred for the indicated time. (Note: Agitation is very important for
the reaction outcome! The reaction mixture has to be vigorously stirred
to obtain high yields and reproducible results.) After allowing the
reaction mixture to cool to room temperature, the teflon stopper was
removed and ethyl acetate (8 mL), distilled water (4 mL), and aqueous 30%
NH4OH (4 mL) were added sequentially. The aqueous layer was extracted
with ethyl acetate (2 x 8 mL). The combined organic layers were dried
over MgSO4, filtered through CeliteTM, and concentrated under reduced
pressure. The residue was purified by silica gel chromatography or
recrystallization. 3-Methyl-2-pivalaminobiphenyl (Table 1, entry 7).
Following the general procedure A using 5 mol% Pd(OAc)2 and 10 mol% DMSO
for 18h at 90°C. Column chromatography: Silica gel, Hexanes/EtOAc,
gradient 4% to 30% EtOAc. White solid; yield: 240 mg (90%),
3-Methyl-2-pivalaminobiphenyl, yield 90% mp 173 °C). 1H NMR (500 MHz,
CDCl3) δ 7.42-7.32 (m, 3H), 7.32-7.28 (m, 2H), 7.27-7.22 (m, 2H),
7.19-7.14 (m, 1H), 6.85 (s, 1H), 2.26 (s, 3H), 1.12 (s, 9H). 13C NMR (125
MHz, CDCl3) δ 176.9, 139.8, 139.7, 136.8, 133.0, 130.2, 129.2, 128.4,
127.8, 127.5, 127.2, 39.2, 27.7, 18.7. IR (KBr plate, CDCl3) ν 3282,
2954, 1646, 1513, 1466, 1365, 1293, 1225, 1178, 1072, 939, 788, 754, 734,
702, 653 cm-1.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM regioselective, optimized on catalyst, additives, gas, reaction
temperature, amount of benzene used, sealed tube used, vigorous stirring
required to obtain high yields and reproducible results, optimization
study

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Synthetic Procedure: Approximately 0.2
g of the cinnamic acid (ca. 1 mmol) is dissolved in 1 mL arene and 4 mL
of triflic acid is added. The mixture is stirred for 6 hrs and poured
over about 15 g of ice. The resulting mixture is extracted twice with
CHCl3 and the organic extracts are washed with water, then brine, and
dried over MgSO4. Concentration with reduced pressure then gives the
products; if necessary, column chromatography is done over silica. ENTRY
12; PRODUCT: 5n, YIELD 92%.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 2.1.3. Synthesis of 2-benzylbenzonitriles 1 by
the Friedel–Crafts reaction: A typical procedure for synthesis of
2-benzyl-1-naphthonitrile 1n To a flask charged with AlCl3 (0.989 g, 7.42
mmol) in dry benzene (9.3 mL) was added 2-(bromomethyl)-1-naphthonitrile
10n (0.911 g, 3.70 mmol) in an ice bath. The reaction mixture was warmed
to room temperature and then heated to reflux for 45 min. When all the
starting materials were consumed, as checked by TLC, the reaction mixture
was cooled to room temperature, poured into ice and then acidified with 1
N HCl. The organic materials were extracted with CH2Cl2. The combined
organic extracts were washed with water and then with brine and dried
over anhydrous MgSO4. The solvents were removed in vacuo and the
resulting crude material was subjected to flash column chromatography
(hexane : EtOAc = 90 : 10). 2-benzyl-1-naphthonitrile 1n (0.711 g, 2.92
mmol) in 79% yield. 2-benzyl-5-hydroxybenzonitrile (1l-OH) 92% yield from
10l (demethylation was concurrently observed under the Friedel–Crafts
reaction conditions) which was converted into 1m by further benzylation;
Gray soild. mp. 137.2-138.7 °C; IR (NaCl) 3065, 3032, 2932, 2874, 2222,
1603, 1568, 1495, 1454, 1244 cm-1; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 4.14 (2H,
s), 5.43 (1H, br), 6.66 (1H, s), 6.73 (1H, dd, J = 8.4, 2.0 Hz),
7.22-7.33 (5H, m), 7.52 (1H, d, J = 8.4 Hz); 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3) δ
40.1, 104.3, 114.3, 117.0, 118.5, 126.8, 128.7, 129.0, 134.9, 138.4,
147.6, 159.5; ESIHRMS: Found: m/z 210.0922. Calcd for C14H12NO: (M+H)+
210.0919.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM Friedel-Crafts reaction (stage 1)

$DATUM Formation of [(C5Me5)2Sm(C6H5)]2, 8, from [(C5Me5)2SmMe]3,2, and Benzene.
Complex 2 (20 mg, 0.015 mmol) was dissolved in neat benzene and stirred
for 30 min at 25 °C. The solution changed from orange to yellow-brown.
Volatiles were removed in vacuo, and [(C5Me5)2Sm(C6H5)]231-33 (21 mg,
92%) was isolated as a glassy yellow brown solid and identified by 1H NMR
spectroscopy. [(C5Me5)2Sm(C6H5)]2 8, yield 92%.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General Procedure for Preparation of 1-Arylbenziodoxolones (2a−o). The
finely crushed, solid 2-iodobenzoic acid 1 or 7 (4.033 mmol) wasmixed
with powdered Oxone (1.5−1.6 g, 2.4−2.6 mmol) in a 100 mL round-bottom
flask and stirred without solvent for 5min using a magnetic stirrer until
a homogeneous reaction mass was formed. Then the reaction mixture was
cooled with ice to 5 °C and under magnetic stirring, precooled to 5 °C.
H2SO4 (total 3.2 mL) was added via syringe by 0.2 mL portions to the
center of the reaction mixture. After addition of each portion of H2SO4,
the reaction mass was mechanically shaken to achieve better mixing; the
color of the resulting mass can vary from pale yellow to brown depending
on the intensity of mixing. After all H2SO4 was added, the magnetic
stirring was continued for 30min at room temperature, themixture was
cooled to 5 °C and CH2Cl2 (4 mL) and ArH (4.0−11.0 mmol) were added. The
magnetic stirring of the resulting mixture was continued at 5 °C for 1 h
and then at room temperature for 2 h. The reaction mixture was recooled
to 5 °Can=CH2Cl2 (10 mL) and then a saturated aqueous solution of NaHCO3
was added in small portions until pH 8.0. The organic layer was separated
and the aqueous layer was additionally extracted with CH2Cl2 (10 mL). The
organic extracts were combined and dried with Na2SO4, the solvent was
evaporated and the crystalline product was dried in vacuum. Additional
purification of products 2 can be performed by crystallization from
water. 1-Phenyl-1H-1λ3-benzo[b]iodo-3(2H)-one (2a). The reaction of
2-iodobenzoic acid 1 (1.00 g, 4.033 mmol), Oxone (1.6 g, 2.6 mmol), H2SO4
(total 3.2 mL) and benzene (0.8 mL) according to the general procedure
afforded crude product 2a, which was further purified by crystallization
from water to give 1-phenyl-1H-1λ3-benzo[b]iodo-3(2H)-one monohydrate.
Crude product 2a: 1.27 g (92%) Purified product 2a: Off-white crystalline
solid, 1.21 g (88%). mp 221−222 °C (from water) (lit.5a mp 220 °C of
monohydrate); 1H NMR (CDCl3, 500 MHz) δ 8.36 (dd, J = 1.5, 7.5 Hz, 1 H),
7.99 (dd, J = 1.0, 7.5 Hz, 2 H), 7.73 (m, 1 H), 7.57 (m, 2 H), 7.52 (m, 1
H), 7.35 (ddd, J = 1.5, 7.0, 8.5 Hz, 1 H), 6.72 (d, J = 8.5 Hz, 1 H); 13C
NMR (CDCl3, 125 MHz) δ 166.8, 137.2, 133.5, 133.4, 132.5, 132.4, 131.7,
130.4, 126.4, 115.7, 115.4.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM green chemistry-reagent
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Preparation and X-ray Structural Study of 1-Arylbenziodoxolones
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Yusubov, Mekhman S.; Yusubova, Roza Y.; Nemykin, Victor N.; Zhdankin,

$DATUM Preparation of (Cp*Ru)3(μ3-CH)(μ 3-η2:η2(⊥)-PhCCMe) (7). Benzene (10 mL)
and μ3-methylidyne- μ3- η2(//)-propyne complexes, (Cp*Ru)3(μ3-CH)(μ
3-η2:(//)-MeCCH)- (μ-H) 2 (6) (50.6 mg, 0.066 mmol), were charged in a
glass autoclave. The reaction vessel was heated at 180 °C for 12 h with
vigorous stirring. After the solvent was removed under reduced pressure,
the residual solid was washed with 5 mL of methanol three times. The
residual solid was then dried under reduced pressure, and 7 was obtained
as a red solid (51.2 mg, 0.061 mmol, 92 % yield). A red single-crystal
used for the diffraction study was prepared from the pentane/methanol
solution of 7 stored at -30 °C. 1H NMR (400 MHz, 23 °C, THF-d8 ): δ 1.41
(s, 15H, C5Me 5 ), 1.72 (s, 30H, C5Me5), 2.28 (s, 3H, PhCCMe), 5.65 (dd,
JH-H = 7.6, 1.0 Hz, 2H, o-Ph), 6.63 (tt, JH-H = 7.2, 1.0 Hz, 1H, p-Ph),
6.94 (dd, JH-H = 7.6, 7.2 Hz, 2H, m-Ph), 17.28 (s, 1H, μ3-CH). 13C NMR
(100 MHz, 23 °C, THF-d8): δ 11.6 (q, JC-H= 125 Hz, C5Me5), 27.5 (q, JC-H
= 126 Hz, PhCCMe), 91.2 (s, C5Me 5), 94.3 (s, C5Me5), 108.9 (s, PhCCMe),
121.3 (d, JC-H = 157 Hz, p-Ph), 124.6 (d, JC-H = 155 Hz, m-Ph), 127.3 (d,
JC-H = 156 Hz, o-Ph), 147.3 (s, ipso-Ph), 223.6 (s, PhCCMe), 348.8 (d,
JC-H = 153 Hz, μ3-CH). IR (ATR, cm-1): 2978, 2952, 2901, 1586, 1477,
1370, 1022, 864. Anal. Calcd for C40H54Ru3 : C, 57.33; H, 6.49. Found C,
57.62; H, 6.15. Crystallographic Data Color:Red, Crystal size (mm) 0.10 ×
0.10 ×0.10, Crystal System :Monoclinic, Space Group :C2/m (#12).Lattice
Parameters,a = 17.418(11) Å b = 18.059(7) Å c = 11.485(6) Å, β =
103.33(5)°, Z value =4.

$DATUM Preparation of trans-[MoCl(N)(κ4-P4)] (3a). To a green suspension of 2a
(740 mg, 0.840 mmol) in THF (50 mL) was added 1,1-dimethylhydrazine (100
μL, 1.32 mmol), and the mixture was stirred at room temperature for 90
min. Volatiles were removed from the resulting orange-red solution under
reduced pressure, and the residue was extracted with benzene (40 mL).
Addition of hexane to the concentrated benzene extract afforded
orange-red crystals of 3a.0.5(C6H6) (664 mg, 92%). trans-[MoCl(N)(κ4-P4)]
(3a) , Yield (664 mg, 92%). 1H NMR (C6D6): δ 2.05- 2.25, 2.35-2.55,
2.75-2.95, 3.35-3.55 (m, 2H each, PCH2), 6.75- 7.15 (m, 20H, aromatic H),
7.45-7.6 (m, 6H, aromatic H), 7.75- 7.85, 8.55-8.65 (m, 4H each, aromatic
H). 13C{1H} NMR (C6D6): δ 66.5, 101.9 (AA'XX' pattern: JAX = 6, JAX'= 94,
JAA' = 23, JXX' = 12 Hz). IR (KBr, cm-1): 994 (v (MoΞ N)). Anal. Calcd
for C49H45ClMoNP4: C, 65.16; H, 5.02; N, 1.55. Found: C, 65.67; H, 5.12;
N, 1.37.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

or Imido Complexes and Their Reactivities

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Typical Procedure for Expeditious Conditions
(Continuous MW Irradiation): Synthesis of 2,4,6-Trimethylbenzophenone
(25) (Table 3, Entry 4). Mesitylene (6) (4.80 g, 40 mmol), benzoyl
chloride (11) (1.40 g, 10 mmol), and iron(III) chloride (162 mg, 1 mmol)
were introduced together in the quartz reactor of the Synthewave
apparatus surrounded by a condenser and a stirrer. The mixture was
irradiated under an incident power of 300 W for 1 min. After cooling, the
conversion rate was determined by analyzing an aliquot of the reaction
mixture by GC, using tetradecane as an internal standard: 99%. The
reaction mixture was quenched with 20 mL of a saturated sodium carbonate
aqueous solution. The layers were separated, and the aqueous layer was
washed three times with 10 mL of dichloromethane. The combined organic
phases were dried over magnesium sulfate and concentrated under reduced
pressure up to elimination of 6 in excess. The crude product was purified
by flash chromatography (silica gel, pentane/ether, 9:1) to give 25 as an
overmelted Solid. Entry 3.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM microwave
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Acylation Reactions under Microwaves. 3. Aroylation of Benzene and Its
Slightly Activated or Deactivated Derivatives

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure A for the arylation of
anilides with benzene: An oven-dried Schlenk tube equipped with a stir
bar and a teflon stopper was cooled to room temperature under vacuum and
backfilled with O2. With the tube open to the air, the anilide (1.00
mmol) and Pd(OAc)2 (11.3-22.6 mg, 5-10 mol%) were added. The tube was
evacuated and backfilled with O2, followed by addition of benzene (1 mL,
~11 equiv), TFA (370 μL, 5.00 equiv), and DMSO (7-14 μL, 10-20 mol%) by
syringe under a positive O2 pressure with the tube open to the air. The
tube was sealed and lowered into a preheated oil bath at 55-100 °C and
stirred for the indicated time. (Note: Agitation is very important for
the reaction outcome! The reaction mixture has to be vigorously stirred
to obtain high yields and reproducible results.) After allowing the
reaction mixture to cool to room temperature, the teflon stopper was
removed and ethyl acetate (8 mL), distilled water (4 mL), and aqueous 30%
NH4OH (4 mL) were added sequentially. The aqueous layer was extracted
with ethyl acetate (2 x 8 mL). The combined organic layers were dried
over MgSO4, filtered through CeliteTM, and concentrated under reduced
pressure. The residue was purified by silica gel chromatography or
recrystallization. 4-Methyl-2-pivalaminobiphenyl (Table 2, entry 2).
Following the general procedure A using 5 mol% Pd(OAc)2 and 10 mol% DMSO
for 18h at 90°C. Column chromatography: Silica gel, Hexanes/EtOAc,
gradient 4% to 25% EtOAc. Off-white solid; yield: 244 mg (91%),
4-Methyl-2-pivalaminobiphenyl, yield 91% mp 77-78 °C). 1H NMR (300 MHz,
CDCl3) δ 8.24 (s, 1H), 7.53-7.33 (m, 6H), 7.14 (d, J = 7.8 Hz, 1H),
7.02-6.96 (m, 1H), 2.41 (s, 3H), 1.10 (s, 9H). 13C NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3) δ
176.6, 138.7, 138.3, 135.1, 129.7, 129.6, 129.6, 129.2, 128.1, 124.9,
121.6, 40.0, 27.6, 21.7. IR (KBr plate, CDCl3) ν 3435, 3258, 2959, 1687,
1618, 1579, 1530, 1495, 1479, 1458, 1416, 1366, 1292, 1184, 1151, 818,
765, 703, 597, 541 cm-1. Anal. Calcd. for C18H21NO: C, 80.86; H, 7.92;
Found: C, 80.64; H, 7.94.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM regioselective, sealed tube used, vigorous stirring required to obtain
high yields and reproducible results
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Twofold C-H Functionalization: Palladium-Catalyzed Ortho Arylation of
Anilides
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Brasche, Gordon; Garcia-Fortanet, Jorge; Buchwald, Stephen L.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Organic Letters (2008), 10(11), 2207-2210

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure of Cross-Coupling Reaction for
Separating Products. A 25 mL Schlenk tube was charged with
1,10-phenanthroline (45 mg, 0.25 mmol), KOt-Bu (225 mg, 2.0 mmol),
benzene or pyridine (5 mL), and aryl halides (0.5 mmol) in glovebox. Then
the tube was removed from the glovebox, and the resulting mixture was
stirred upon visible light irradiation (providing 400 mW cm-2 visible
light) for 24 h. The reaction was quenched with water in excess and the
residue was extracted with copious ethyl acetate. The combined organic
phase was concentrated under vacuum. The crude product was purified by
semipreparative HPLC (60% MeCN, 0.1% TFA) to give desired product.
Semipreparative HPLC was performed using an ODS column (ODS-A, 10 × 250
mm, 5 μm) at 5 mL/min. 1H NMR and 13C NMR were recorded on a BRUKER
BIOSPIN AVANCE III spectrometer using TMS as the internal standard.
4-Cyanobiphenyl (3h)[6] 1H NMR (500 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 7.43 (t, J = 7.5 Hz,
1H), 7.49 (t, J = 7.0 Hz, 2H), 7.59-7.61 (m, 2H), 7.68-7.74 (m, 4H). 13C
NMR (125 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 110.9, 119.0, 127.3, 127.5, 127.7, 128.8,
129.2, 132.6, 139.1, 145.6.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM photochemical, alternative preparation shown, Schlenk flask used,
glovebox used, alternative reaction conditions shown, visible light used
(420 nm)

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):SOL(1):CAS_RN
$DATUM 64-17-5
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Step 1: A mixture of benzaldehyde (15 ml, 0.10
mol) and hydrazine hydrate (5 ml, 0.1 mol) was stirred at RT in ethanol
(15 ml) for 8-9 h. After the reaction was completed (monitored by TLC),
ethanol was removed from the mixture under reduced pressure. The product
on recrystallisation from diethyl ether gave yellow crystals of
N,N'-bis(1-methyl)azines 2a (Scheme 2). Step 2: To a 250-ml round-bottom
flask, a mixture of 1.33 g (0.05 mol) of N,N'-bis (1-methyl) azines 2a
and benzene or toluene (1.57 g, 0.02 mol) was added. Ionic liquid [tbaim]
Cl2/ZnCl2 (1.32 g, 0.01 mol was then added, and the mixture was refluxed
for 8-12 h. When the reaction was completed (monitored by TLC), enough
water is added in multiple (50 ml) and extracted with diethyl ether. The
organic layer was dried with anhydrous Na2SO4 and filtered. The solvent
was evaporated off, and the crude product purified by column
chromatography using silica gel as the solid phase and hexane as eluent
to give 3a (Scheme 3). Other compounds 3b-g were synthesized in similar
manner using compound 2a and various selected aromatic hydrocarbons.
Characterization data are presented as shown below.
4-Chlorophenyl-1-phenylmethane 3b: yellow crystals, yield 91%. m.p.
109-10°C; IR (KBr): 2,902; 3,044 cm-1; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): 1.28 (d,

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Step 1: A mixture of benzaldehyde (15 ml, 0.10
mol) and hydrazine hydrate (5 ml, 0.1 mol) was stirred at RT in ethanol
(15 ml) for 8-9 h. After the reaction was completed (monitored by TLC),
ethanol was removed from the mixture under reduced pressure. The product
on recrystallisation from diethyl ether gave yellow crystals of
N,N'-bis(1-methyl)azines 2a (Scheme 2). Step 2: To a 250-ml round-bottom
flask, a mixture of 1.33 g (0.05 mol) of N,N'-bis (1-methyl) azines 2a
and benzene or toluene (1.57 g, 0.02 mol) was added. Ionic liquid [tbaim]
Cl2/ZnCl2 (1.32 g, 0.01 mol was then added, and the mixture was refluxed
for 8-12 h. When the reaction was completed (monitored by TLC), enough
water is added in multiple (50 ml) and extracted with diethyl ether. The
organic layer was dried with anhydrous Na2SO4 and filtered. The solvent
was evaporated off, and the crude product purified by column
chromatography using silica gel as the solid phase and hexane as eluent
to give 3a (Scheme 3). Other compounds 3b-g were synthesized in similar
manner using compound 2a and various selected aromatic hydrocarbons.
Characterization data are presented as shown below. 1-[1-(4-Methoxy
phenyl)-1-phenylmethane: yellow crystals, yield 91%. m.p. 124-125 °C; IR
(KBr): 2,930; 2,837; 3,040 cm-1; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): 7.10-8.17 (m,
11H, Ar-H), 4.28 (s, 3H); 13C NMR: 38.23, 56.5, 115.2, 126.23, 128.22,
129.1, 134.5, 135, 159.05; Anal. Calcd. for C18H16O: C, 87.07; H, 6.49.
Found: C, 87.36; H, 6.44%.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General method B, for preparation of
heterocyclic alcohols (9-13): The N-heterocyclic alcohol (1 mmol) is
dissolved in 3 ml C6H6; CF3SO3H (3ml, 33mmol) is added slowly with
stirring. The reaction mixture stirred for overnight at 60°C and then the
reaction mixture poured on ice. More CHCl3 (ca. 30 ml) is then added and
the aqueous layer is mare basic with 10M NaOH. Separation of the organic
phase is followed by washings with water, and then twice with saturated
brine. The organic solution is dried with MgSO4, filtered, and
concentrated with rotary evaporator. If necessary, the product may be
further purified by silica gel chromatography (hexane: ethyl acetate).
2,2'-(biphenyl-4-ylmethylene)dipyridine (9).
2,2'-((1-phenylnaphthalen-2-yl)methylene)bis(1-methyl-1H-benzo[d]imidazole)
(11). Using general method B, compound 11 is isolated as a brown solid
(Rf 0.19, 2:1 hexanes: ethyl acetate): MP 233-234 °C. 1H NMR (300 MHz,
CDCl3) δ 3.37 (s, 6H), 5.85 (s, 1H), 7.14-7.18 (m, 2H), 7.23-7.31 (m,

was dissolved in CH2Cl2 (1 mL), and benzene (6 μL, 0.0673 mmol) was then
added. The solution was stirred for 3 h at ambient temperature, during

precipitate formed, which was collected by filtration and washed with

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: [{(η 6-Benzene)Ru(η
5-C5Me4CH2)}N(CH3)(CH2CH3)]Cl, [10]- Cl. To 1a prepared from 1 (50.0 mg,
81.5 μmol) in 3 mL of CH3CN was added N,N-ethylmethylamine (69.8 μL,
0.815 mmol) in a 20 mL glass reaction vessel, which was sealed, heated
(ca. 10 min, 85 °C), and subsequently cooled to room temperature.
Potassium tert-butoxide (18.3 mg, 0.163 mmol) was then added, and the
solution was heated for an additional 30 min. An excess of benzene (ca. 5
mL) and H2O (ca. 7 mL) were then added to the solution, and the vessel
was sealed and reacted until near colorless (ca. 3 h at 85 °C). The
aqueous layer was separated, and the organic layer was extracted with
H2O. The combined aqueous layers were evaporated under reduced pressure.
The residual crude solid was dissolved in ethanol and filtered to remove
unwanted KCl. Additional unwanted byproducts were precipitated with the
addition of minimal amounts of diethyl ether and were removed by
filtration. The solvent was then removed under reduced pressure,
resulting in [10]Cl as an oily, tan-colored solid (52.8 mg, 79% yield).
[η 5-{1-((2,3,4,5-Tetramethylcyclopentadienyl)methyl)pyridin- 2-one}Ru(η6
-benzene)][PF6], [15][PF6]. A solution of 2-hydroxypyridine (77.5 μL,
0.815 mmol) and potassium tert-butoxide (18.3 mg, 0.163 mmol) in 500 μL
of CH3CN (heterogeneous mixture) was added dropwise to a solution of 1a
prepared from 1 (50.0 mg, 81.5 μmol) in 1.5 mL of CH3CN. The reaction
vessel was sealed and heated for 10 min (ca. 85 °C). The resulting
solution was further reacted with benzene following the procedure
described for [10]Cl, and the product was isolated according to the
procedure described for [H · 11b][PF6]3, giving [15][PF6] as a white
powder (82.0 mg, 91% yield). white powder 13C NMR ((CD3)2CO, 75.5 MHz): δ
162.95, 141.302, 139.41, 121.52, 106.86, 99.21, 98.54, 95.13, 89.16,
45.31, 11.75, 11.01. ESI-MS: (102Ru) 407.9 (C21H24NORu requires 408.1).
Anal. Calcd (%) for C21H24F6NOPRu: C, 45.66; H, 4.38; N, 2.54. Found: C,
45.78; H, 4.23; N, 2.59.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM sealed vessel used

$DATUM [(η-Tetramethylcyclopentadienyl)(η-benzene)iron] hexafluoro-phosphate,
[(η-C5Me4H)Fe(η-C6H6)]PF6 ([1]PF6). A solution of Br2 (0.6 g, 3.8 mmol)
in CH2Cl2 was added dropwise to a solution of [(η-C5Me4H)Fe(CO)2]2 (1.7
g, 3.6 mmol) in CH2Cl2 (20 mL). The reaction mixture was stirred for 1 h
and concen-trated. Dry AlCl3 (5 g, 37.5 mmol) and benzene (20 mL) were
added to the residue. The reaction mixture was stirred at room
temperature for 16 h and then refluxed for 5 h. On cooling to 0 °C, it
was carefully hydrolyzed with water. The aqueous layer was separated and
filtered. The product was precipitated by adding aqueous NH4PF6. The
resulting yellow precipitate was filtered off, washed with water, and
dried in vacuo. The crude product was reprecipitated from acetone with
ether. The complex [1]PF6 (2.65 g, 91%) as a yellow solid. Found (%): C,
44.74; H, 4.53. C15H19F6FeP. Calculated (%): C, 45.03; H, 4.79. 1H NMR
(acetone-d6), δ: 2.01 (s, 6 H, C5Me4H); 2.02 (s, 6 H, C5Me4H); 5.00 (s, 1
H, C5Me4H); 6.17 (s, 6 H, C6H6).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Procedure for the synthesis of isoflavones (4) The corresponding
3-dimethylamino-1-(2-hydroxyphenyl) propenones (2, 0.5mmol) and iodine
(1.0mmol) were added to the corresponding solvent (40mL) in 50 mL quartz
tubes. The reaction mixture was irradiated with a mercury lamp (500 W),
and the environment temperature was kept about 20 °C by means of a quartz
glass internal cold finger. The mixture was stirred for 6–20 h until the
staring material disappeared (monitored by TLC using EtOAc and petroleum
ether = 1:5 as the mobile phase). After finishing the reaction, the
mixture was treated with 10% NaHSO3 to remove excess iodine and washed
with water, and then, the organic layer was concentrated under reduced
pressure to remove solvent. Then, the residue was purified by flash
chromatography on silica gel (petroleum ether and ethyl acetate from
volume ratio of 80:1 to 30:1). Desired product 4. Isoflavone (4a). [1]
Yield (98.5 mg) as a colorless solid. M.p. 133-135 °C; 1H NMR (300 MHz,
DMSO-d 6) δ 8.53 (s, 1H), 8.15 (d, 1H, J = 7.8 Hz), 7.83 (m, 1H), 7.68
(d, 1H, J = 7.8 Hz), 7.39~7.61 (m, 6H). 13C NMR (75 MHz, DMSO-d 6) δ
175.1, 155.6, 154.6, 134.2, 131.8, 128.9, 128.2, 127.9, 125.5, 125.4,
123.9, 123.8, 118.3; IR ν (cm-1) 3049, 1638, 1567, 1490, 1465, 1430,
1379, 1356, 1286, 1229, 1160, 1103, 1014, 908, 883, 760; HRMS (ESI+) m/z
calcd. for C15H10NaO2 [M+Na]+: 245.0578, found: 245.0565.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM photochemical, optimization study, optimized on stoichiometry, mercury
lamp (500W) used, optimized on stoichiometry of reactant and reagent

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Synthetic Procedure (Products 14-26).
Approximately 0.2 g of the olefin is suspended in 2 mL of benzene and 3
mL of TfOH is added. After being stirred for at least 3 h, the mixture is
poured over ice, and it is made basic with concentrated NaOH. The mixture
is then extracted with CHCl3 and the organic phase is washed with brine,
dried with MgSO4, and concentrated under vacuum.
Ethyl(2-methyl-2-phenylpropyl)amine (21), yield 91% 1H NMR (CDCl3, 300
MHz) δ 1.01 (t, J = 6.6 Hz, 3H), 1.23 (s, 1H), 1.36 (s, 6H), 2.56 (q, J =
6.6 Hz, 2H), 2.75 (s, 2H), 7.15-7.40 (m, 5H) ppm. 13C NMR (CDCl3, 125
MHz) δ 15.3, 27.7, 38.8, 45.0,62.4, 126.0, 126.2, 128.5, 148.1 ppm. MS
m/z (EI) 177 (M+), 91, 58. HRMS (DEI) calcd for C12H20N 178.159575 (MH+),
found 178.159111.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for the Preparation of
Condensed Products 10-19. A 0.2 g portion of the acetyl-substituted
heteroarene was dissolved in 1.0 mL of C6H6, and to this solution was
added 5.0 mL of triflic acid. This mixture was stirred at room
temperature (6 was reacted at 50 °C) for 4-12h and then poured over
several grams of ice. The resulting solution was made basic with
concentrated NaOH and extractedwith CHCl3. The organic phase was washed
with H2O and brine and then dried with MgSO4. Removal of the solvent
under reduced pressure then provided the product. The product (s) was
then purified by recrystallization or column chromatography.
2,4-Dimethyl-5-(1,1-diphenylethyl)thiazole, yield 91%. mp 58-61 °C
(CHCl3); 1H NMR δ 1.90 (s, 3H), 2.19 (s, 3H), 2.54 (s, 3H), 7.20-7.28 (m,
10); 13C NMR δ 17.5, 18.8, 31.3, 48.7, 126.6, 127.9, 128.2, 140.6, 147.4,
147.9, 161.4; EI MS 293 (M+); HRMS m/z calcd for C19H19NS 293.1238, found
293.1234.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for Pd(OAc)2-catalyzed
oxidative cross-coupling of polyfluoroarenes with benzene. Under air
atmosphere, Pd(OAc)2 (0.06 mmol, 14 mg) and Ag2CO3 (0.90 mmol, 248 mg)
were added into a dried Schlenk tube. The tube was stopped and degassed
with N2 for three times. Then HOAc (0.60 mmol, 36 mg), polyfluoroarene 1
(0.60 mmol), and diisopropyl sulfide (0.60 mmol, 71 mg) were added by
syringe, followed by benzene (4.0 mL, 75 equiv). The mixture was stirred
under N2 atmosphere at 120 °C for 20 h (unless otherwise specified), and
then cooled down to room temperature. The resultant mixture was filtered
through a short plug of silica gel and then concentrated in vacuo. The
product 3 was further purified through flash chromatography on silica gel
with petroleum ether. 2,3,5,6-Tetrafluoro-4-(trifluoromethyl)biphenyl
(3i). This compound was prepared according to the general procedure
described above using 131 mg 2,3,5,6-tetrafluorobenzotrifluoride with
benzene, and purified by flash chromatography to afford 162 mg white
crystal with 91% yield. R f = 0.82 (petroleum ether). 1H NMR (300 MHz,
CDCl3): δ = 7.45-7.55 (m, 5H). 13C NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 119.0 (m),
122.7, 124.9 (m), 126.0, 128.8, 129.9-130.0 (m), 144.2 (dm, J F = 242.6).
19F NMR (283 MHz, CDCl3): δ = -63.8~-63.6 (m, 2F), -63.1~-62.7 (m, 2F),
21.6 (t, J F = 21.9, 3F). MS (EI): found: 294 (M+), calcd for C13H5F7
(M+): 294.03.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Palladium-Catalyzed Cross-Coupling of Polyfluoroarenes with Simple Arenes
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Li, Hu; Liu, Jia; Sun, Chang-Liang; Li, Bi-Jie; Shi, Zhang-Jie
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Organic Letters (2011), 13(2), 276-279

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the condensation
reaction of aldehydes/ dicarboxaldehydes with aromatics, using BF3-H2O as
the acid catalyst Aldehydes or dicarboxaldehydes (1mmol) and neat
aromatics (2 mL for liquid aromatics; 4 eqv. for solid aromatics) were
taken in a sealed pressure tube. To this mixture, BF3-H2O (50 eqv., 4.2
g) was added and the mixture was stirred and heated at the required
temperature under closed condition till the reaction is completed.
Completion of the reaction was monitored by TLC and GCMS. The reaction
mixture was then poured into ice-water (10 mL) and extracted with
dichloromethane (3x 20 mL). Combined organic layer was washed with aq.
NaHCO3 solution, then with brine solution, dried over anhydrous Na2SO4
and then solvent was removed under reduced pressure to get the crude
product. The crude product was further purified by column chromatography
over silicagel (65-250 mesh) using hexane-ethyl acetate 2-10% as eluent.
Products were characterized and identified by analyzing their spectral
data (1H, 13C, 19F NMR data, GCMS and HRMS).
1-(Diphenylmethyl)-2-bromobenzene (7f) 1H NMR δ 5.94 (s, 1H), 6.92 (dd, J
= 7.78 Hz, J = 1.65 Hz, 1H), 7.01 (ddd, J = 7.78 Hz, J = 7.80 Hz, J =1.65
Hz, 1H), 7.04-7.06 (m, 4H), 7.12 (ddd, J = 7.60 Hz, J = 7.60 Hz, J = 1.28
Hz, 1H), 7.16-7.19 (m, 2H), 7.20-7.25 (m, 4H), 7.52 (dd, J = 7.88 Hz, J =
1.28 Hz, 2H); 13C NMR δ 55.9, 125.5, 126.4, 127.1, 128.0, 128.3, 129.6,
131.3, 133.0, 142.5, 143.1; MS (EI), m/z 322.8 (M·+), 241.4 (M·+-Br),
164.0 (M·+-Br-Ph).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM pressure tube used, no solvent
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM BF3-H2O Catalyzed Hydroxyalkylation of Aromatics with Aromatic Aldehydes
and Dicarboxaldehydes: Efficient Synthesis of Triarylmethanes,
Diarylmethylbenzaldehydes, and Anthracene Derivatives
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR

$DATUM Transformations of compounds 1a—c and 5a—c on treatment with aluminum
halides in the presence of benzene (general procedure). To a mixture of
AlBr3 or AlCl3 (5.0 mmol) in benzene (10 mL), compound 1a—c or 5a—c (1.0
mmol) was added, the mixture was stirred at 20—80 °C for 1—10 h (see
Table 1, entries 2, 3, 5—7, and 9—12). The products were isolated as
described above. 4,4-Diphenyl-3,4-dihyroquinolin-2-one (6a), Yield 91%

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure for the CF3SO3H-Catalyzed Reactions.
In a 50mL glass pressure tube (with Teflon screw cap), ~100 mg of the
pyrazine derivative is dissolved in 2mL benzene, and 5mL triflic acid is
then slowly added. The sealed tube is then heated to 80°C. After 4h, tube
is cooled and the product mixture is poured onto ice. The resulting
solution is neutralized by 10.0 M NaOH solution, and extracted twice with
CHCl3. The organic phase is washed with brine and then dried over
anhydrous Na2SO4. After concentration, the products are then purified by
flash column chromatography (etehr:hexane).
2-(1,2-Diphenyl-ethyl)-pyrazine (2c). Clear, brown oil; 1H NMR 500 MHz,
CDCl3, δ: 3.45 (dd, 1H, J = 7.0Hz, 13.6Hz), 3.72 (dd, 1H,J = 8.6Hz,
13.6Hz), 4.46 (t, 1H, J = 8Hz, 7.5Hz), 7.11 (d, 2H, J =7.2Hz), 7.18 (d,
1H, J =7.1Hz), 7.21-7.28 (m, 2H), 7.35 (t, 2H, J = 7.4Hz, 7.7Hz), 7.42
(d, 2H,J = 7.5Hz), 8.39 (d, 1H, J = 1.8Hz), 8.59 (s, 1H), 8.43 (s, 1H)
13C NMR 125 MHz, CDCl3, δ: 41.2, 53.0, 126.2, 127.0, 128.2, 128.3, 128.7,
129.1, 139.8, 142.3, 142.5, 144.1, 145.0, 158.5. Low resolution mass
spectrum (EI) m/z: 260 (M+), 183, 91. HRMS: calcd for C18H16N2: 260.1313,
measured 260.1320.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Synthetic Procedure (Products 14-26).
Approximately 0.2 g of the olefin is suspended in 2 mL of benzene and 3
mL of TfOH is added. After being stirred for at least 3 h, the mixture is
poured over ice, and it is made basic with concentrated NaOH. The mixture
is then extracted with CHCl3 and the organic phase is washed with brine,
dried with MgSO4, and concentrated under vacuum. 16, yield 91%

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: The imidazole substrate (0.1 g) is dissolved
in benzene (or other arene; 1.0 mL) and CF3SO3H(1-2 mL) is added. The
reaction is stirred at least 2 h, and then the mixture is poured over
several grams of ice. The mixture is made basic (pH paper) with the slow
addition of 10 M NaOH. The resulting solution is extracted twice with
CHCl3, and the combined organic extracts are further washed with water
(once) and then brine (twice). If purification is necessary, the product
mixture is subjected to column chromatography (silica gel; hexane/
ether). 2-(1,2-Diphenylethyl)-1-methyl-1H-imidazole (42). Using general
procedure A, compound 40 is reacted to give product 42 as the major
product. Compound 42: 1H NMR (CDCl3): δ 3.26 (s,3H), 3.29 (dd, J = 13.4,
8.0, Hz, 1H), 3.75 (dd, J = 13.4, 8.1 Hz, 1H), 4.14-4.17 (m, 1H), 6.75
(s, 1H), 7.03 (d, J = 7.0 Hz, 2H), 7.06 (s, 1H), 7.13-7.29 (m, 8H). 13C
NMR (CDCl3): δ 32.4, 42.2, 46.1, 120.8, 126.1, 126.7, 127.1, 128.0,
128.1, 128.5, 129.3, 140.1, 141.3, 149.1. Low resolution MS (EI): 262
(M+), 171, 130. High resolution MS (EI), C18H18N2 calcd: 262.14700, found
262.14696.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General method A, for preparation of
heterocyclic alcohols (2, 13-15): The N-heterocyclic trifluoromethyl
ketone (1 mmol) is dissolved in 2 mL CHCl3 and 2 mL C6H6; CF3SO3H (2 mL,
22 mmol) is added slowly with stirring. After a two hour reaction at
25°C, the mixture is poured on ice. More CHCl3 (ca. 30 mL) is then added
and the aqueous layer is made basic with 10 M NaOH. Separation of the
organic phase is followed by washings with water, and then twice with
saturated brine. The organic solution is dried with MgSO4, filtered, and
concentrated on a rotary evaporator. If necessary, the product may be
further purified by silica gel chromatography (hexanes:ether). Note: this
procedure has not been optimized and some substrates (i.e. 1) are found
to give better product yields with longer reaction times.
1-(benzo[d]thiazol-2-yl)-2,2,2-trifluoro-1-phenylethanol (13): Using
general procedure A, compound 13 is isolated as a colorless crystals,
Yield 91% (Rf 0.38, 2:1 hexanes:ethyl ether): MP 70-73°C. 1H NMR, 500
MHz, CDCl3, δ: 5.63 (s, 1H), 7.45-7.51 (m, 1H), 7.55-7.58 (m, 1H),
7.89-7.93 (m, 3 H), 8.13 (d, J= 8.2 Hz, 1H). 13C NMR, 125 MHz, CDCl3, δ:
78.6 (q, JC-F = 30 Hz), 121.8, 123.7, 123.9, 124.4 (q, JC-F = 285 Hz),
126.2, 126.7, 128.7, 129.5, 136.1, 136.3, 151.1, 168.5. EI-MS: 309 (M+),
269, 240, 162, 105. HRMS clacd for C15H10ONF3S 309.04352, found
309.04316.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedures for the BF3-H2O catalyzed
reactions of trifluoroacetaldehyde methyl hemiacetal and
difluoroacetaldehyde ethyl hemiacetal 3a and 3b with arenes The
trifluoroacetaldehyde methyl hemiacetal 2a, 80% (w/w in H2O), (0.3 g,
1.85 mmol) was mixed with excess of arene (10 mmol) in a pressure tube.
The mixture was cooled to 0 °C and BF3-H2O (5 g, 58 mmol) was added
slowly. For difluorobenzene and nitrobenzene 7 g and 10 g of BF3-H2O were
used, respectively. The mixture was stirred for the required period of
time (Table 1) at room temperature or higher, depending on the nature of
the substrate. The progress of all reactions was monitored by TLC (4:1
hexane/ethyl acetate) and GC-MS. After completion of the reactions, the
mixtures were poured over ice ( ≈ 25g), neutralized with sodium
bicarbonate and extracted with CH2Cl2 (3 x 15 mL). The organic extracts
were combined, washed with water and dried over anhydrous Na2SO4. The
solvent was removed by vacuum evaporation and crude products were
purified with column chromatography on silica gel (70-230 mesh) using
hexane/ethyl acetate as eluent. The products were characterized by
spectral analysis (NMR, GC-MS and HRMS).
1,1,1-Trifluoro-2,2-diphenylethane (3a)16a, 23, yield 90%. 1H NMR (400
MHz, CDCl3): δ 4.66 (q, J(H-F) = 10.07 Hz, 1H), 7.24-7.36 (m, 10H); 13C
NMR (100.5 MHz, CDCl3): δ 55.53 (q, 2J(C-F) = 27.47 Hz), 126.23 (q,
1J(C-F) = 280.00 Hz), 128.23, 129.03, 129.42, 135.41; 19F NMR (376 MHz,
CDCl3): δ -66.26 (d, J(H-F) = 9.92 Hz); GC-MS (EI ), m/z, 236.7 (M+).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM slow addition of boron trifluoride - water complex, pressure tube used,
Friedel-Crafts reaction, no solvent
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Fluoroanalogs of DDT: Superacidic BF3-H2O Catalyzed Facile Synthesis of
1,1,1-Trifluoro-2,2-diarylethanes and 1,1-Difluoro-2,2-diarylethanes
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Prakash, G. K. Surya; Paknia, Farzaneh; Mathew, Thomas; Mloston,
Gzregorz; Joschek, Jens P.; Olah, George A.

$DATUM Kinetic Studies: Rate Determination for Activation of C6D6 by
TpRu[P(OCH2)2(OCCH3)](NCMe)Ph (4). A solution of TpRu[P-
(OCH2)2(OCCH3)](NCMe)Ph (4; 0.0115 g, 0.0203 mmol), acetonitrile (3.4 μL,
0.070 mmol), and a crystal of hexamethylbenzene (as an internal standard)
in 2mL of C6D6 (22.6 mmol) was equally divided and transferred into four
J. Young NMR tubes. The solutions were heated to 60 °C in a
temperature-regulated oil bath. 1H NMR spectra were periodically acquired
through 3 half-lives (using a pulse delay of 5 s). Relative to the
internal standard hexamethylbenzene, the rates of Ru-Ph/Ru-Ph-d5 exchange
were followed by integration of the ortho phenyl resonance at 7.69 ppm.
Compound 4-d5, yield 90%.

$DATUM Addition of Hydrogen to 1. Compound 1 (11.6 mg, 0.0067 mmol) was
dissolved in 25 mL of hexane. With stirring, hydrogen was then allowed to
purge through the solution at 25 °C for 4 h. The solvent was removed in
vacuo, and the product was separated by TLC using a 3:1 hexane/methylene
chloride solvent mixture. Pt3Re2(CO)6(PBut 3)3(μ-H)6, yield 90% IR νCO
(cm-1, in hexane) 2009 (s), 1914 (vs); 1H NMR (400 MHz, toluened8, 25 °C,
TMS) δ = 1.50 ppm (d, 3J(P,H) ) 13 Hz, 81 H, CH3), -4.34 ppm (quartet,
1J(Pt,H) ) 723 Hz, 2J(P,H) ) 4 Hz, 6H, hydride); 13C{1H} NMR (162 MHz,
toluene-d8, 25 °C, 85% ortho-H3PO4) 111.42 ppm (m, 3P) [2J(Pt,Pa) ) 222
Hz, 3J(Pa,Pb) ) 56 Hz] [1J(Pt,Pb) ) 2986 Hz, 3J(Pa,Pb) ) 56 Hz]
[1J(Pt,Pb) ) 3208 Hz, 3J(Pa,Pb) ) 56 Hz], see the Discussion for an
explanation; ES+/MS m/z calcd for M + H, [Pt3- Re2P3O6C42H87 + H]+, 1739,
found 1739. The isotope pattern is consistent with the presence of three
platinum and two rhenium atoms. Anal. Cacld for Pt3Re2(CO)6(PBut
3)3(μ-H)6.C6H6: 31.73, C; 5.16, H. Found: 31.94, C; 5.21, H.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of
compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in
arene (3.0 mL) was added boron trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The
mixture was cooled to 0°C and then homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl
compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by drop over 10 min. The temperature was
slowly brought to rt in 1h. The reaction mixture was stirred at rt for
specified time. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC using
ethyl acetate and hexane as eluents. After completion of the reaction,
the product was extracted with ethyl acetate, washed with brine and
water. The organic layer was dried (Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the
crude product, which was purified by short column chromatography over
silica gel to give the title compounds.
2-Hexyl-6-(4-nitro-phenyl)-4-phenyl tetrahydropyran (19b): Semisolid, 90%
yield 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.89 (t, J = 7.2 Hz, 3 H), 1.26-1.39 (m,
8 H), 1.41-1.64 (m, 3 H), 1.66-1.75 (m, 1 H), 1.90-1.95 (m, 1 H),
2.08-2.13 (m, 1 H), 2.99 (tt, J = 12.4 and 4.0 Hz, 1 H), 3.63-3.69 (m, 1
H), 4.62 (dd, J = 11.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 7.21-7.34 (m, 5 H), 7.56 (d, J =
8.4 Hz, 2 H), 8.19 (d, J = 8.8 Hz, 2 H). 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ
14.2, 22.8, 25.6, 29.5, 31.9, 36.4, 38.7, 41.3, 42.1, 78.2 (2C), 123.6,
126.5, 126.6, 126.8, 128.7, 145.2, 147.1, 150.7. IR: 3063, 3029, 2930,
2856, 1602, 1519, 1454, 1346, 1132, 1083, 1014, 853, 748, 698 cm-1 .

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for the Preparation of
Condensed Products 10-19. A 0.2 g portion of the acetyl-substituted
heteroarene was dissolved in 1.0 mL of C6H6, and to this solution was
added 5.0 mL of triflic acid. This mixture was stirred at room
temperature (6 was reacted at 50 °C) for 4-12h and then poured over
several grams of ice. The resulting solution was made basic with
concentrated NaOH and extractedwith CHCl3. The organic phase was washed
with H2O and brine and then dried with MgSO4. Removal of the solvent
under reduced pressure then provided the product. The product (s) was
then purified by recrystallization or column chromatography.
2,6-Bis-(1,1-diphenylethyl)pyridine, yield 90%. mp 138-140 °C (CHCl3); 1H
NMR δ 2.13 (s, 6H), 6.84 (d, J = 7.8 Hz, 2H), 7.06-7.10 (m, 8H),
7.18-7.26 (m, 12H), 7.40 (t, J = 7.8, 1H); 13C NMR δ 29.2, 55.2, 120.0,
125.6, 127.5, 128.7, 135.7, 148.7, 165.2; EI MS 439 (M+); HRMS m/z calcd
for C33H28N (M- H) 438.2222, found 438.2212.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM α , α-Dimethyl phenethyl alcohol acetate Add benzene (150 ml) and
anhydrous AlCl3 (25.7 g, 0.19 mol) to one flask, and stir to partially
dissolve AlCl3. Cool the mixture to 6 °C, then add 2 g propylene
glycol-methyl acetate; continue to cool until the temperature falls below
2 °C. Then, add methyl allyl acetate (18.5 g, 0.16 mol) dropwise while
stirring and keeping the temperature between 0 and 5 °C. The addition is
completed in 2 h. At the end of the reaction, 300 ml ice-water is added
dropwise to the mixture slowly, else the reaction is violent. Continue to
stir for 30 min, then extract the water layer with benzene (30 ml x 2).
Then, combine the organic layer and add MgSO4. Remove excess benzene in
vacuum to obtain α , α -dimethyl phenyl acetate ethanol (2) Yield of 27.5
g (89.7 %)
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM regioselective, controlled addition, Friedel-Crafts reaction, reactant
assumed
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
