$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Reaction of α -Acylnitromethanes with Benzene
in Acid; General Procedure To a solution of 2a-l (1.5 mmol) and benzene
(6.5 mL, 75 mmol, 50 equiv) in anhydrous CH2Cl2 (1.5 mL), TFSA (1.3 mL,
15 mmol, 10 equiv) was added at 0 °C (ice-water bath) under Ar, and the
mixture was stirred for 20 min. The mixture was poured into ice-water
(100 mL) and the mixture was extracted with CHCl3 (3 × 100 mL). The
organic layer was washed with brine (2 × 50 mL), and dried over Na2SO4.
The solvent was evaporated and the resulting crude product was purified
by flash column chromatography (typically with EtOAc-n-hexane, 1:10→ to
give 3a-l. The reaction yields are shown in Table 3.
3-Trifluoromethylbenziloxime (3g) Recrystallized from n-hexane. Colorless
needles. Yield 90%. mp 100-101 °C. 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 8.28 (br
s, 1 H), 8.24 (br s, 1 H, OH), 8.19 (br d, J = 7.6 Hz, 1 H), 7.84 (br d,
J = 7.6 Hz, 1 H), 7.61 (t, J = 7.6 Hz, 1 H), 7.58-7.55 (m, 2 H),
7.48-7.45 (m, 3 H). 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 190.1, 155.7, 137.3,
133.6, 133.6, 131.0, 130.2, 129.6, 129.4, 129.0, 128.3, 127.3. Anal.

$DATUM [Cp*Ir(IMe)Ph(solv)]+[MeB(C6F5)3]- (7b). A solution of 3b (47.8 μmol) in
CD2Cl2 was prepared in a J. Young NMR tube as described above. Benzene
(0.467 g, 5.97 mmol, 125 equiv) was added to this solution by static
vacuum transfer. After 24 h, the volatile components were removed under
reduced pressure to afford an oily, dark reddish-brown residue. After
CD2Cl2 was added to this material by static vacuum transfer and shaking.
Yield 90% 1H NMR (500 MHz, CD2Cl2, 25 °C): δ 7.36 (s, free C6H6, 1.3
equiv), 7.30-7.15 (m, 5 H, Ir-Ph), 7.13 (s, 2 H, NHC C-H), 3.54 (s, 6 H,
NHCN-Me), 1.65 (s, 15 H, Cp*). 13C{1H} NMR (126 MHz, CD2Cl2, 25 °C): δ
175.64 (s, NHC Ccarbene), 165.18 (s, Ir- Ph ipso), 138.87 (s, Ir-Ph),

$DATUM Complex IIIa. To a solution of 1.00 g (2.71 mmol) of dioxide Ia in 20 ml
of benzene was added at stirring 0.89 g (8.13 mmol) of N-cyanopiperidine
in 5 ml of benzene. The reaction mixture was heated for 6 h at 60°C. The
solvent was distilled off. The residue was treated with a mixture
hexane-ether, 2:1 (10x5 ml). We obtained complex IIIa. Yield 1.80 g
(90%). mp 150°C. IR spectrum, ν , cm-1: 1185, 1385 (SO2), 1625, 1725
(C=N). 1H NMR spectrum, δ , ppm: 1.50-1.65 m [18H, 3(CH2)3], 3.60-3.85 t
[12H, 3(CH2)2N], 7.33 s (3H, 0.5 C6H6). Mass spectrum, m/z: 369 [M1]+,
330 [M2]+, 147 [CCl3CO]+, 110 [(CH2)5NCN]+, 84 [(CH2)5N]+, 78 [M3]+, 77
[C6H5]+, 64 [SO2]+, 36 [Cl]+. Found, %: C 40.60; H 4.55; Cl 29.14; N
15.51; S 4.30. C50H66Cl12N16O6S2. Calculated, %: C 40.64; H 4.50; Cl
28.86; N 15.65; S 4.34.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of
compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in
arene (3.0 mL) was added boron trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The
mixture was cooled to 0°C and then homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl
compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by drop over 10 min. The temperature was
slowly brought to rt in 1h. The reaction mixture was stirred at rt for
specified time. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC using
ethyl acetate and hexane as eluents. After completion of the reaction,
the product was extracted with ethyl acetate, washed with brine and
water. The organic layer was dried (Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the
crude product, which was purified by short column chromatography over
silica gel to give the title compounds.
4-(4-Phenyl-tetrahydropyran-2-yl)-benzoic acid methyl ester (9b): Solid,
90% yield M. P. 61.2- 63.4°C; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.71 (q, J =
11.2 Hz, 1 H), 1.82-1.95 (m, 2 H), 2.09 (dquint, J = 13.2 and 1.6 Hz, 1
H), 2.97 (tt, J = 11.6 and 4.4 Hz, 1 H), 3.76 (dt, J = 11.6 and 3.2 Hz, 1
H), 3.90 (s, 3 H), 4.30 (ddd, J = 11.6, 4.0 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 4.54 (dd, J
= 11.2 and 2.4 Hz, 1 H), 7.19-7.33 (m, 5 H) 7.45 (d, J = 7.6 Hz, 2 H),
8.02 (d, J = 7.6 Hz, 2 H). 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ 33.3, 41.6, 42.1,
52.1, 68.7, 79.4, 125.7, 126.6, 126.8, 128.7, 129.2, 129.8, 145.3, 148.0,
167.0. IR: 3061, 3029, 2950, 2845, 1722, 1611, 1435, 1279, 1112, 1089,
855, 757, 701 cm-1 . Anal. Calcd for C19H20O3: C, 77.00; H, 6.80. Found:
C, 77.12; H, 6.75.

$DATUM General Procedure for Acid-Promoted Cyclization in Benzene. To a solution
of diene 2 (0.200 g, 1.05 mmol) in benzene (5 mL) was added
trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (0.111 mL, 1.26 mmol) at 0°C. The reaction
was warmed to 21°C and stirred for 3 h. The solution was quenched with a
saturated solution of NaHCO3 (10 mL). The mixture was extracted with
hexanes (3x20 mL), and the combined organic extracts were dried with
MgSO4, filtered, and concentrated in vacuo to give a crude yellow oil.
Purification by flash column chromatography on silica gel (19:1
hexanes/ethyl acetate) afforded the trimethylphenyladamantanone 4a.
1,3,5-Trimethyl-7-phenyladamantan-2-one, 4a. Light yellow oil, yield
0.253 g, 0.94 mmol (90%). 1H NMR (500 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.38−7.31 (m, 4H),
7.23 (bt, J = 7.0 Hz, 1H), 1.98 (bd, J = 12 Hz, 2H), 1.88−1.85 (m, 4H),
1.64 (bd, J = 12.5 Hz, 2H), 1.57−1.54 (m, 4H), 1.01 (s, 9H). 13C NMR (125
MHz, CDCl3) δ 218.5, 147.7, 128.3, 126.2, 124.9, 52.5, 51.5, 48.1, 45.9,
38.4, 32.1, 28.8, 22.6. HRMS (ESI, m/z): 269.1895; calcd for C19H24OH
(M+H)+, 269.1905.

$DATUM [(C5Me5)2U]2(μ-η6:η6-C6H6), 1, from (C5Me5)3U. A solution of (C5Me5)3U
(123 mg, 0.191 mmol) in C6H6 was added dropwise to a stirred suspension
of KC8 (29 mg, 0.215 mmol) in C6H6. After 3 h, black and white solids
were separated from the solution by centrifugation. The solvent was
removed by rotary evaporation, affording [(C5Me5)2U]2-(μ-η6:η6-C6H6) (94
mg, 90%) as a brown solid. [(C5Me5)2U]2(μ-η6:η6-C6H6), yield (94 mg, 90%)
1H NMR (C6D6, 298 K): δ 3.06 (s, 60H, C5Me5, 1JC,H 124 Hz, ∆ν1/2 15 Hz),
-99.4 (s, 6H, C6H6, ∆ν1/2 30 Hz). (C7D8, δ 2.09, 298 K): δ 2.97 (s, 60H,
C5Me5, 1JC,H 125 Hz, ∆ν1/2, 5 Hz), -98.9 (s, 6H, C6H6, ∆ν1/2 28 Hz). 13C
NMR (C6D6, 298 K): δ -25.7 (s-sp3 C-C5Me5), 281.7 (sp2 C-C5Me5), 455 (s,
C-C6H6), assignments confirmed by HMQC. FT-IR: 2961(s), 2910(s), 2856(s),
2725(w), 1494(m), 1440(s), 1378(s), 1324(m), 1262- (s), 1089(b), 1069(s),
1023(s), 949(w), 911(w), 802(s), 663(s), 586- (w). Magnetic
susceptibility, 298 K: χm = 186.2 10-6 μeff = 2.1 μB. Anal. Calcd for
U2C46H66: U, 43.49. Found: U, 43.75. The hydrolysis and deuteriolysis of
the black and white arene insoluble solids formed C5Me5H and C5Me5D,
which were identified by GC-MS.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: GP-1 (General Procedure for Friedel-Crafts
Alkylation and Acylation of Ethyl Cinnamates): To an oven dried Schlenk
tube under nitrogen atmosphere, were added ester 1 (100 mg, 0.42-0.57
mmol), arene 2 (in case of benzene, toluene and xylene 12 equivalents and
for other electron rich arenes 1.5 equivalents were used for 1 equivalent
of the ester 1) and DCE (2 mL), followed by the addition of triflic acid
[3 equiv (i.e 1.26-1.71 mmol)]. The resultant reaction mixture was
stirred at 80 °C for 12-24 h. Progress of the reaction was monitored by
TLC until the reaction was completed. The reaction mixture was quenched
by the addition of aqueous NaHCO3 and extracted with DCM (3 × 20 mL). The
combined organic layers were washed with saturated NaCl solution, dried
(Na2SO4) and concentrated under reduced pressure. Purification of the
residue by silica gel column chromatography (petroleum ether/ethyl
acetate) furnished the compound. Product: 3c, Yield: 90 %.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM Schlenk tube used, Friedel-Crafts reaction, optimization study, optimized
on reagent
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Superacid-promoted dual C-C bond formation by Friedel-Crafts alkylation
and acylation of ethyl cinnamates: synthesis of indanones
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Ramulu, Bokka Venkat; Reddy, Alavala Gopi Krishna; Satyanarayana, Gedu
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Synlett (2013), 24(7), 868-872

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Typical Procedure for Biaryls. To a mixture of
manganese( III) acetate15 (330 mg, 1.24 mmol Mn(OAc)3•2H2O) in 10 mL of
benzene was added phenylboronic acid (50 mg, 0.41 mmol), and the
resulting mixture was refluxed for 30 min (formation of the products was
monitored by TLC and GCMS). After the completion of the reaction, the
mixture was filtrated through a pad of silica using hexane or petroleum
ether as the eluent. Concentration under reduced pressure furnished the
biphenyl 2a (62 mg, 95%, solid), confirmed by NMR, IR, and GC-MS. 2b,
yield (90%).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Generation of Aryl Radicals from Arylboronic Acids by Manganese(III)
Acetate: Synthesis of Biaryls and Heterobiaryls
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Demir, Ayhan S.; Reis, Oemer; Emrullahoglu, Mustafa
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Journal of Organic Chemistry (2003), 68(2), 578-580

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Synthetic Procedure (Products 14-26).
Approximately 0.2 g of the olefin is suspended in 2 mL of benzene and 3
mL of TfOH is added. After being stirred for at least 3 h, the mixture is
poured over ice, and it is made basic with concentrated NaOH. The mixture
is then extracted with CHCl3 and the organic phase is washed with brine,
dried with MgSO4, and concentrated under vacuum.
1-(2-Phenylpropyl)-1H-imidazole (22), yield 90% 1H NMR (CDCl3, 300 MHz) δ
1.27 (d, J = 6.9 Hz, 3H), 3.02-3.10 (m, 1H), 4.02 (d, J = 7.5 Hz, 3H),
6.72 (s, 1H), 6.97 (s, 1H), 7.60-7.23 (m, 2H), 7.18-7.36 (m, 3H) ppm. 13C
NMR (CDCl3, 125 MHz) δ 18.8, 41.9, 54.5, 119.4, 127.2, 127.3, 129.0,
129.4, 137.6, 142.9 ppm. MS m/z (EI) 186 (M+), 105, 82. HRMS (EI+) calcd
for C12H14N2 186.115699, found 186.115742.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General Synthetic Procedure (Products 2, 12, 14, 16, 22, 24, 26, 28):
Approximately 0.2 g of the amide (ca. 1 mmol) is dissolved in 1 mL arene
and 4 mL of triflic acid is added. The mixture is stirred for 6 hrs at
25°C and poured over about 15 g of ice. The resulting mixture is
extracted twice with CHCl3 and the organic extracts are washed with
water, then brine, and dried over MgSO4. Concentration with reduced
pressure then gives the products; if necessary, column chromatography is
done over silica. 1-Acetyl-4,4-diphenylpiperidine (3), yield 90% MP (80%
hexane:20% CHCl3): 103-105°C; 1H NMR (300 MHz, CHCl3) δ, ppm 2.08 (s,
3H), 2.37-2.44 (m, 4H), 3.48-3.51 (m, 2H), 3.67-3.69 (m, 2H), 7.00 - 7.32
(m, 10H); 13C NMR (125 MHz, CHCl3) δ, ppm 21.7, 36.0, 36.9, 38.8, 43.8,
45.2, 126.4, 127.2, 128.9, 146.5, 169.1; EI MS 279 (M+).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General method B, for preparation of
heterocyclic alcohols (9-13): The N-heterocyclic alcohol (1 mmol) is
dissolved in 3 ml C6H6; CF3SO3H (3ml, 33mmol) is added slowly with
stirring. The reaction mixture stirred for overnight at 60°C and then the
reaction mixture poured on ice. More CHCl3 (ca. 30 ml) is then added and
the aqueous layer is mare basic with 10M NaOH. Separation of the organic
phase is followed by washings with water, and then twice with saturated
brine. The organic solution is dried with MgSO4, filtered, and
concentrated with rotary evaporator. If necessary, the product may be
further purified by silica gel chromatography (hexane: ethyl acetate).
2,2'-(biphenyl-4-ylmethylene)dipyridine (9).
2,2'-(biphenyl-4-ylmethylene)bis(1-methyl-1H-benzo[d]imidazole) (10).
Using general method B, compound 10 is isolated as a brown oil (Rf 0.31,
2:1 hexanes: ethyl acetate): 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ 3.78 (s, 6H), 6.46
(s, 1H), 7.28-7.39 (m, 9H), 7.46 (t, J=6.9 Hz, 2H), 7.60 (dd, J=8.4, 1.5
Hz, 4H), 7.80-7.83 (m, 2H); 13C NMR: δ 30.9, 45.0, 109.5, 120.0, 122.1,
122.8, 127.1, 127.6, 127.7, 128.6, 128.9, 135.2, 136.5, 140.3, 140.7,
142.4, 151.6. Low resolution TOF-MS (ES+): 429 (MH+), 313, 291. High
resolution TOF-MS (ES+), calculated for C29H25N4 429.2079, found
429.2072.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General procedure for the synthesis of compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a
mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in arene (3.0 mL) was added boron
trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The mixture was cooled to 0°C and then
homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by
drop over 10 min. The temperature was slowly brought to rt in 1h. The
reaction mixture was stirred at rt for specified time. The progress of
the reaction was monitored by TLC using ethyl acetate and hexane as
eluents. After completion of the reaction, the product was extracted with
ethyl acetate, washed with brine and water. The organic layer was dried
(Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the crude product, which was purified by
short column chromatography over silica gel to give the title compounds.
2-(4-Nitro-phenyl)-4-phenyl-tetrahydropyran(2b): Solid, 90% yield M. P.:
77-78°C; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.1.64 (q, J = 12.4 Hz, 1 H),
1.85-1.95 (m, 2 H), 2.10 (dquint, J = 13.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 2.98 (tt, J
= 12.4 and 4.0 Hz, 1 H), 3.76 (dt, J = 11.6 and 3.2 Hz, 1 H), 4.30 (ddd,
J = 11.6, 4.0 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 4.57 (dd, J = 11.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H),
7.19- 7.33 (m, 5 H) 7.53 (d, J = .8 Hz, 2 H), 8.17 (d, J = .8 Hz, 2 H).
13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ 33.2, 41.7, 42.0, 68.7, 78.8, 123.7, 126.5,
126.7, 126.8, 128.8, 145.0, 147.2, 150.3. IR: 3085, 2941, 2848, 1633,
1603, 1520, 1347, 1130, 1106, 1088, 850, 748 cm-1 . Anal. Calcd for
C17H17NO3: C, 72.07; H, 6.05; N, 4.94. Found: C, 72.18; H, 6.21; N, 4.88.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the condensation
reaction of aldehydes/ dicarboxaldehydes with aromatics, using BF3-H2O as
the acid catalyst Aldehydes or dicarboxaldehydes (1mmol) and neat
aromatics (2 mL for liquid aromatics; 4 eqv. for solid aromatics) were
taken in a sealed pressure tube. To this mixture, BF3-H2O (50 eqv., 4.2
g) was added and the mixture was stirred and heated at the required
temperature under closed condition till the reaction is completed.
Completion of the reaction was monitored by TLC and GCMS. The reaction
mixture was then poured into ice-water (10 mL) and extracted with
dichloromethane (3x 20 mL). Combined organic layer was washed with aq.
NaHCO3 solution, then with brine solution, dried over anhydrous Na2SO4
and then solvent was removed under reduced pressure to get the crude
product. The crude product was further purified by column chromatography
over silicagel (65-250 mesh) using hexane-ethyl acetate 2-10% as eluent.
Products were characterized and identified by analyzing their spectral
data (1H, 13C, 19F NMR data, GCMS and HRMS).
4-(Diphenylmethyl)benzaldehyde (8a) 1H NMR δ 5.65 (s, 1H), 7.14-7.16 (m,
4H), 7.26-7.28 (m, 2H), 7.31-7.35 (m, 6H), 7.74- 7.77 (m, 2H), 9.91 (s,
1H); 13C NMR δ 56.7, 126.6, 128.4, 129.2, 129.6, 129.9, 134.6, 142.6,
150.9, 191.7; MS (EI), m/z 272.6 (M·+), 242.8 (M·+-CHO), 165.0
(M·+-Ph-CHO); HRMS (EI) m/z 272.1201, calculated for C20H16O 272.1201.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM pressure tube used, no solvent

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the synthesis of
compounds 1b-21b and 22-25: To a mixture of aldehydes (1.0 equiv.) in
arene (3.0 mL) was added boron trifluoride etherate (1.2 eqiuv.). The
mixture was cooled to 0°C and then homoallyl alcohol (1.0 equiv) in aryl
compound (2.0 mL) was added drop by drop over 10 min. The temperature was
slowly brought to rt in 1h. The reaction mixture was stirred at rt for
specified time. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC using
ethyl acetate and hexane as eluents. After completion of the reaction,
the product was extracted with ethyl acetate, washed with brine and
water. The organic layer was dried (Na2SO4) and evaporated to leave the
crude product, which was purified by short column chromatography over
silica gel to give the title compounds.
2-(3-Nitro-phenyl)-4-phenyl-tetrahydropyran (3b): Semisolid, 90% yield 1H
NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.70 (q, J = 12.4 Hz, 1 H), 1.86-1.98 (m, 2 H),
2.13 (dquint, J = 13.2 and 2.0 Hz, 1 H), 2.99 (tt, J = 11.6 and 4.0 Hz, 1
H), 3.78 (dt, J = 11.2 and 3.6 Hz, 1 H), 4.33 (dd, J = 10.0 and 2.8 Hz, 1
H), 4.58-4.61 (m, 1 H), 7.21-7.36 (m, 5 H), 7.48-7.52 (t, J = .0 Hz, 1
H), 7.71(d, J = .0 Hz, 1 H), 8.12 (d, J = .0 Hz, 1 H), 8.29 (s, 1 H). 13C
NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ 33.1, 41.6, 41.9, 68.7, 78.5, 120.9, 122.3,
126.6, 126.8, 128.7, 129.3, 131.9, 145.0, 145.1, 148.3. IR: 3086, 3062,
3028, 2917, 2848, 1602, 1526, 1349, 1130, 1091, 845, 807, 759 cm-1 .

H, 6.18; N, 5.03.

$DATUM General procedure C: Arylation of o-tolyl dimethylcarbamate (1a) with
benzene In a one-dram vial equipped with a Teflon cap was added o-tolyl
dimethylcarbamate (1a) (35.8 mg, 0.2 mmol), Pd(OAc)2 (4.5 mg, 0.02 mmol,
10 mol%), Pd(OAc)2 (4.5 mg, 0.02 mmol, 10 mol%), Na2S2O8 (142.8 mg, 0.6
mmol), and benzene (1 mL). Subsequently, trifluoroacetic acid (76 μL, 1
mmol) was added. The vial was sealed with a Teflon cap and stirred on a
heating block at 70 °C for 24 h. A second portion of Pd(OAc)2 (2.2 mg,
0.01 mmol, 5 mol%) was added and heating was maintained for an additional
12 h. After cooling to ambient temperature, the resulting mixture was
diluted in 5 mL EtOAc and washed with 5 mL sat'd NaHCO3. The aqueous
phase was extracted with 3 x 10 mL EtOAc. The combined organic extracts
were dried over Na2SO4, concentrated in vacuo and the resulting residue
was purified by preparative thin-layer chromatography (eluent:
hexane/EtOAc = 3:1, v/v) to afford the phenylated product 2a as a
colorless oil (45.8 mg, 90%). 3-Methylbiphenyl-2-yl dimethylcarbamate
(2a): Prepared from 1a according to general procedure C until a total of
39 h had elapsed (90%). Colorless oil. 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.56 (d,
J= 2.0 Hz, 1H), 7.45 (d, J=8.3 Hz, 1H), 7.28-7.23 (m, 2H), 7.20-7.16 (m,
2H), 2.98 (s, 3H), 2.89 (s, 3H), 2.25 (s, 3H). 13C{1H} NMR (100 MHz,
CDCl3) δ 154.1, 147.1, 138.3, 135.4, 131.6, 130.1, 129.0, 128.3, 127.9,
127.0, 125.5, 36.6, 36.2, 16.5. HRMS (ESI) m/z calc'd for C16H18NO2
[M+H]+: 256.1332; found: 256.1322.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Procedure for the synthesis of isoflavones (4)
The corresponding 3-dimethylamino-1-(2-hydroxyphenyl) propenones (2,
0.5mmol) and iodine (1.0mmol) were added to the corresponding solvent
(40mL) in 50 mL quartz tubes. The reaction mixture was irradiated with a
mercury lamp (500 W), and the environment temperature was kept about 20
°C by means of a quartz glass internal cold finger. The mixture was
stirred for 6–20 h until the staring material disappeared (monitored by
TLC using EtOAc and petroleum ether = 1:5 as the mobile phase). After
finishing the reaction, the mixture was treated with 10% NaHSO3 to remove
excess iodine and washed with water, and then, the organic layer was
concentrated under reduced pressure to remove solvent. Then, the residue
was purified by flash chromatography on silica gel (petroleum ether and
ethyl acetate from volume ratio of 80:1 to 30:1). Desired product 4.
Isoflavone (4a). [1] 6-Chloroisoflavone (4e). [1] Yield 90% (116.5 mg) as
a colorless solid. M.p. 195-196 °C; 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ 8.27 (d,
1H, J = 2.4 Hz), 8.02 (s, 1H), 7.62 (dd, 1H, J = 9.0, 2.4 Hz), 7.59 –7.51
(m, 2H), 7.49–7.38 (m, 4H); 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3) δ 175.0, 154.5,
153.1, 133.9, 131.4, 131.3, 128.9, 128.6, 128.4, 125.8, 125.6, 125.5,
119.8; IR ν (cm-1) 3086, 3053, 1640, 1604, 1564, 1496, 1467, 1357, 1272,
1222, 1191, 1122, 1070, 1024, 901, 821, 795, 740, 694, 635, 615; HRMS
(ESI+) m/z calcd. for C15H9ClNaO2 [M+Na]+: 279.0189, found: 279.0203.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM photochemical, mercury lamp (500W) used
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM An efficient strategy to syntheses of isoflavones
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Liu, Longzhu; Wang, Qiuya; Zhang, Zunting; Zhang, Qiong; Du, Zichao; Xue,
Dong; Wang, Tingting

pyridyl)boratophenylmethylplatinate(II), nBu4N(dp-BMe2)PtPh(Me), 13 From
complex 10, benzene and 3 equ of water. Solid nBu4N(dp-BMe2) (40 mg,
0.091 mmol) was added to precursor Pt2Me4(SMe2)2 (26.1 mg, 0.091 mmol Pt)
and both solids dissolved in 2 mL of benzene as in the synthesis of 11
from complex 7. After 10 minutes the solvent was removed under high
vacuum to give dimethyl complex 10, pure by NMR. Benzene and 5μL of water

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: III. Experimental Procedure for the Oxidative
Amination with Various Nitrogen Sources: To a 5 mL screw-capped vial
equipped with a 15 x 10 mm spinvane triangular-shaped Teflon stirbar,
were added imide (0.3 mmol, 1 equiv), PhI(OAc)2 (483 mg, 1.5 mmol, 5
equiv) and benzene (1.5 mL). The resulting mixture was sealed with a
Teflon-lined cap and stirred at 140 °C for 4 h in an oil bath with
vigorous stirring. The reaction mixture was cooled to room temperature,
filtered through a plug of silica and washed with EtOAc (30 mL). The
filtrate was concentrated, and evaporated to dryness under high vacuum.
The desired product was purified by flash column chromatography using
indicated eluents. N-Phenylsaccharine (Table 2, 3h), white solid, yield
90%. m.p. 167-169 °C; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 8.12 (d, J = 8.2 Hz, 1H),
7.96 (d, J = 6.8 Hz, 1H), 7.89-7.85 (m, 2H), 7.54-7.52 (m, 5H); 13C NMR
(100 MHz, CDCl3) δ 158.3, 137.6, 135.0, 134.4, 130.0, 129.9, 128.73,
128.66, 127.1, 125.6, 121.2; IR (Film) 3091, 1740, 1653, 1496, 1337,
1311, 1272, 1186, 1099 cm-1; HRMS (FAB) m/z calcd. For C13H9NO3S [M]+:
259.0303, found: 259.0305.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Reactions of alcohols 1-7, 16: The alcohol (1
mmol) is dissolved in 1mL of C6H6 and 3 mL of CF3SO3H is added. After at
least 2 hrs of stirring, the mixture is poured over ice, and the solution
is made basic with 10 M NaOH. Extraction with CHCl3 is followed by
aqueous washes of H2O (1x) and brine (2x), and then drying with anhydrous
Na2SO4. The product is then purified by chromatography (hexane : EtOAc)
or recrystallization.
2,4-Dimethyl-5-(1-methyl-2,2-diphenyl-2-deuterium-ethyl)-thiazole (9).
Oil. 1H NMR (CDCl3, 500 MHz) δ, ppm:1.25-1.26(m,3H), 2.20-2.21(d, J =
3.8Hz, 3H), 2.56(s,3H), 3.89-3.91(t, J = 6.5Hz, 1H), 7.06-7.08(m,1H),
7.15-7.25(m, 5H), 7.33- 7.37(m, 2H), 7.42-7.44(m, 2H). 13C NMR (CDCl3,
500 MHz) δ, ppm: 15.1, 19.2, 37.0-37.1(d, J = 40Hz), 60.6-61.2 (m),
126.3, 126.6 127.9, 128.1, 128.2, 128.7, 136.8, 143.2-143.4(dd, J 1 =
64Hz, J 2 = 20Hz), 146.6, 161.8. HRMS calcd for C20H20DNS: 308.1457.
Measured: 308.1459.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Typical Procedure for the BF3.OEt2-Catalyzed
Friedel-Crafts Reaction. To benzene (3 mL) were added
3-phenylprop-2-yn-1-yl trichloroacetimidates 2a (107 mg, 0.387 mmol) and
BF3. OEt2 (15 μL, 0.116 mmol). The solution was stirred for 5 min at room
temperature, the solvent was removed in vacuo, and the crude product was
purified by column chromatography on silica gel with petroleum ether to
give 1,3-diphenylprop-1-yne 3a (63 mg, 85%) as a light yellow oil.
1-(3-p-Tolylprop-2-ynyl)benzene (3b). 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.42-7.07
(m, 9H), 3.80 (s, 2H), 2.31 (s, 3H); 13C NMR (75 MHz CDCl3) δ 137.7,
136.8, 131.5, 128.9, 128.5, 127.9, 126.5, 120.5, 86.7, 82.7, 25.7, 21.4;
IR (neat, cm-1) 3029 (w), 1605 (w), 1509 (m); HRMS calcd for C16H14
206.1096, found 206.1091.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: [(C6F5)3B(IDipp)Ir(COD)] (1b): 441 mg of 3b
(0.42 mmol, 1 equiv.) and 140 mg of [Ir(COD)Cl]2, (0.21 mmol, 0.5 equiv.)
were dissolved in THF (15 mL) and the reaction mixture was stirred for 24
hours. The solvent was removed in and resulting mass was carefully dried
in vacuo. The red residue was dissolved in dichloromethane (5 mL),
filtered through Celite and the solvent was removed in vacuo. The
resulting gum was dissolved in benzene (3 mL),. From this solution,
yellow prisms of complex 4 crystallized at room temperature within 24
hours. [(C6F5)3B(IDipp)IrH2(C6H6)] (10): 200 mg of 1b (0.17 mmol, 1
equiv.) were suspended in benzene (10 mL) and the reaction mixture was
stirred for 2 hours under 1 atm of dihydrogen. The resulting clear
colorless solution was evaporated and dried in vacuoto afford
analytically pure 9. 1H NMR (600 MHz, CD2Cl2): δ = 7.47 (two triplets (∆
= 1.7 Hz), 2 H, 3J(1H, 1H) = 7.7 Hz, p-Dipp+p-Dipp*), 7.26 (d, 3J(1H, 1H)
= 7.7 Hz, 2 H, m-Dipp), 7.17 (br d, 3J(1H, 1H) = 7.2 Hz, 2 H, m-Dipp*),
6.31 ((br s (v1/2 ≈ 15.4 Hz), 1H, CH=C-B), 5.75 (s, 6 H, C6H6), 2.93
(spt, 3J(1H, 1H) = 6.4 Hz, 2 H, CH(CH3)2), 2.48 (spt, 3J(1H, 1H) = 7.0
Hz, 2 H, CH(CH3)2), 1.27 (d, 3J(1H, 1H) = 6.8 Hz, 6 H, CH(CH3)2), 1.22
(br s (v1/2 ≈ 17.8 Hz), 6 H, CH(CH3)2), 1.00 (d, 3J(1H, 1H) = 6.8 Hz, 6
H, CH(CH3)2), 0.81 (br s (v1/2 ≈ 15.2 Hz), 6 H, CH(CH3)2), -16.21 (s, 2
H, IrH2) ppm. 13C NMR (151 MHz, CD2Cl2): δ= 149.6 (dm, 1J(13C, 19F) ~ 240
Hz, C6F5), 147.4-147.7 (m, ips o-ipp*), 148.1-149.6 (m, CH=C-B), 146.7
(s, ips o-ipp), 145.8 (s, N-C-N), 140.4 (s, o-ipp*), 139.1 (dm, 1J(13C,
19F) ~ 244 Hz, C6F5), 138.7 (s, o-ipp*), 137.2 (dm, 1J(13C, 19F) ~ 250
Hz, C6F5), 131.7 (br s (v1/2 ≈ 15.8 Hz), CH=C-B), 130.7 and 130.2
(p-Dipp+p-Dipp*), 125.1 (br s (v1/2 ≈ 11.8 Hz), m-Dipp*), 124.8 (s,
m-Dipp), 97.1 (s, C6H6), 28.9 (s, CH(CH3)2), 28.8 (s, CH(CH3)2*), 26.1
(s, CH(CH3)2*), 25.5 (s, CH(CH3)2), 23.3 (br s (v1/2 ≈ 15.4 Hz),
CH(CH3)2*), 22.8 (s, CH(CH3)2) ppm. 11B NMR (96 MHz, CDCl3): δ= -15.1 (br
s, v1/2 ≈ 16.4 Hz) ppm. 19F NMR (188 MHz, CDCl3): δ= -122.6 -135.4 (br,
o-6F5), -162.1 (t, 3J( 19F, 19F) = 20.7 Hz, p-C6F5), -166.1 (br s (v1/2 ≈
58.7 Hz), m-C6F5) ppm EA Anal. Calcd for C51H43BF15IrN2: C, 52.27; H,
3.70; N, 2.39. Found: C, 52.54; H, 3.80; N, 2.31 MS (ESI+, CH3CN): m/z
(%) 1135.2704 (5, Calc. for M-C6H6+CH3CN: 1135.2705), 1158.2616 (67,
Calc. for M-C6H6+ CH3CN+Na: 1158.2603), 1174.2350 (65, Calc. for
M-C6H6+CH3CN+K: 1174.2342), 1199.2865 (100, Calc. for M-C6H6+2CH3CN+Na:
1199.2868). formula: C65.5H63BF15IrN2O0.5; fw: 1374.19; crystal system:
triclinic;crystal size, mm: 0.09 × 0.07 × 0.05; space group P1-; a, Å :
11.2463(4); b, Å : 23.0795(6); c, Å : 25.3189(6); α, deg: 64.391(2); β,
deg: 88.146(2); γ, deg: 78.446(2); V, Å 3: 5795.1(3); Z: 4.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Reaction of 3 with C6H6 in the presence of NIPr2Et. A 100 mL thick-walled
glass reaction vessel was charged with 3 (50 mg, 0.0814 mmol),
diisopropylethylamine (14.18 μL, 0.0814 mmol), benzene (15 mL), and a
Tefloncoated magnetic stir bar. The vessel, which contained a
heterogeneous slurry at 25°C, was then sealed with a Teflon stopcock. The
reaction mixture was stirred vigorously and heated to 150°C, affording a
homogeneous red solution. Over the course of 36 h the solution color
gradually changed from red to purple, the color of complex 5. After 36 h,
the reaction was allowed to cool and the reaction volatiles were
subsequently removed by lyophilization from a frozen benzene solution.
The fine purple powder that remained was analyzed by 1H NMR spectroscopy
(CDCl3) and established a 93% conversion from 3 to 5 (internal standard),
production of a stoichiometric equivalent of [HNipr2Et][OTf], and an
unidentified BOA-containing side product (7 %) by 1H NMR spectroscopy.
complex 5. yield 93%
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM 150° for 36 h

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General Synthetic Procedure: Approximately 0.2 g of the cinnamic acid
(ca. 1 mmol) is dissolved in 1 mL arene and 4 mL of triflic acid is
added. The mixture is stirred for 6 hrs and poured over about 15 g of
ice. The resulting mixture is extracted twice with CHCl3 and the organic
extracts are washed with water, then brine, and dried over MgSO4.
Concentration with reduced pressure then gives the products; if
necessary, column chromatography is done over silica. PRODUCT: 4g, YIELD
90%
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM chemoselective, regioselective
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Superacid-Catalyzed Reactions of Cinnamic Acids and the Role of
Superelectrophiles
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION

$DATUM (e). [RhIr(CO)3(κ1-dppm)(μ-SiHPh)2(dppm)] (7). Method 1. In an NMR tube,
under an Ar atmosphere, [RhIr(H)2(CO)2-( μ-SiHPh)(dppm)2] (4) (30mg,
0.024mmol) was dissolved in 0.7 mL of CD2Cl2. The tube was then evacuated
and filled to a pressure of 1 atm with CO.A total of 3.0 μL (1
equivalent) of PhSiH3 was added via a microliter syringe to the NMR tube.
After 18 h, complex 7 formed almost quantitatively (97%) according to
31P{1H} NMR spectroscopy. 31P{1H} NMR (27 °C; CD2Cl2, 202.1 MHz): δ 15.6
(PA, 1P, ddd, 1JRhP(A) = 105 Hz, 2JP(A)P(B)=108 Hz, 3JP(A)P(D) = 5 Hz),
3.4 (PD, 1P, dddd, 2JP(C)P(D) = 41Hz, 3JRhP(D)=6Hz,
2JP(B)P(D)=13Hz),-10.5 (PB, 1P, ddd, 4JP(B)P(C)=4 Hz), -24.5 (PC, 1P,
dd). 1H NMR (27 °C; CD2Cl2, 399.8 MHz): δ 6.20 (Si-H, dd, 1H, 1JSi-H =
190.0 Hz, 3JP(D)H = 24.0 Hz, 3JP(A)H = 19.0 Hz), 5.80 (Si-H, dd, 1H,
1JSi-H = 190.0 Hz, 3JP(D)H=3JP(A)H=5.3 Hz), 4.21 (CH2, m, 1H), 3.73 (CH2,
m, 1H), 3.10 (CH2, m, 1H), 2.80 (CH2, m, 1H). 2H{1H} NMR (27 °C; CD2Cl2,
61.4 MHz): δ 6.24 (b, Si-D, 1D), 5.75 (b, Si-D, 1D). 13C{1H}NMR(27
°C;CD2Cl2, 100.5MHz): δ 198.0 (Rh-CO, dd, 1C, 1JRhC=57.0 Hz, 2JPC=10.0
Hz), 195.0 (Rh-CO, dd, 1C, 1JRhC=75.0 Hz, 2JPC=22.0 Hz), 186.0 (Ir-CO,
bs, 1C), 37.6 (CH2, m, 1C), 34.2 (CH2, m, 1C). 29Si{1H} NMR(27 °C;
CD2Cl2, 78.5MHz, DEPT, gHSQC): δ 101.8 (m), 136.6 (m).

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for stoichiometric reactions
of 2a: Complex 2a (20.0 mg, 0.0169 mmol) and Si2Me6 (1.0 μL) were
dissolved in 0.4 mL of THF-d8. A 1H-NMR spectrum was acquired. To this
solution was added the combination of a primary or secondary amine and
triethylamine, an alkali metal alkoxide, sodium 2-methylpentanoate, or an
alkali metal malonate as nucleophile. Reactions of the primary amines
were conducted with 5.0 equiv of the primary amine and 1.2 equiv of the
tertiary amine; the other reactions were conducted with 1.2 equiv of the
nucleophile. The resulting mixture was stirred for 5 min. A solution of
PPh3 (4.9 mg, 0.019 mmol) in 0.1 mL of THF-d8 was then added, at which
point the solution turned yellow. A second 1H-NMR spectrum was acquired,
and the yields of the organic product were determined by integration of
the two 1H-NMR spectra vs the Si2Me6 internal standard. The identity of
the allylation products was confirmed by comparing the GC retention times
with commercially available material or independently synthesized
products. Yield 91%

$DATUM Antimony Corroles.
(5,10,15-Trispentafluorophenylcorrolato)(trans-bispyridine)antimony(III)
(2a). An about 3-fold excess of SbCl3 (86 mg, 0.38 mmol) was added to a
pyridine solution (5 mL) of 1 (100 mg, 0.126 mmol) in one portion. TLC
examinations (silica gel, n-hexane/CH2Cl2)2:1) revealed that the starting
material was fully consumed within 10 min at 100 °C. Solvent evaporation
and crystallization from CH2Cl2/pyridine/n-heptane mixtures yielded 109
mg (95%) of (tpfc)Sb(pyr), 2a. UV-vis (pyridine) λ max (ε × 10-4): 405
(3.43), 425 (14.78), 606 nm (1.22). MS-Maldi (TOF LD-) (m/z): 914 ([M- -
2 pyridine], 100%). 1H NMR (pyridine-d 5, 300 MHz): δ 9.39 (overlapping
doublets, 4H), 9.13 (d, J = 4.5 Hz, 2H), 9.03 (d, J = 3.9 Hz, 2H). 1H NMR
(C6D6, 300 MHz): δ 8.94 (d, J = 4.2 Hz, 2H), 8.79 (d, J = 4.8 Hz, 2H),
8.54 (d, J = 4.8 Hz, 2H), 8.47 (d, J = 4.2 Hz, 2H). 19F NMR (pyridine-d
5, 282 MHz): δ -138.35 (dd, 3 J = 24.7 Hz, 4 J = 7.1 Hz, 2F, o-F),
-138.67 (unresolved dd, 2F, o-F), -138.85 (dd, 3 J = 24.7 Hz, 4 J = 7.1
Hz, 2F, o-F), -154.05 (dt, J = 21.4 Hz, 2F, p-F), -154.33 (t, J = 21.2
Hz, 1F, p-F), -162.77 (dt, J = 22.6 Hz, 6F, m-F). 19F NMR (C6D6, 282
MHz): δ -137.9 (dd, 3 J = 24.7 Hz, 4 J = 7.1 Hz, 3F, o-F), -138.32 (dd, 3
J = 24.7 Hz, 4 J = 7.1 Hz, 1F, o-F), -138.47 (dd, 3 J = 24.7 Hz, 4 J =
7.1 Hz, 2F, o-F), -152.67 (dt, J = 21.2 Hz, 3F, p-F), -161.93 (dt, 3 J =
22.6 Hz, 4 J = 7.3 Hz, 4F, m-F), -162.37 (t, 3 J = 22.6 Hz, 4 J = 7.1 Hz,
2F, m-F).

solvate (II). A mixture of 0.17 g of salicylic acid, 0.55 g of I, and 5
ml of benzene in a glass ampule was heated at 80°C for 10 min. The
solvent was slowly evaporated at room temperature to obtain. Compound
VII, yield 96%. mp 131°C; Found, % C: 80.47; H: 5.68; Formula; С31Н25О2Р;

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Synthesis of
Pentacarbonyl{(3R,4S,9S,10R)-3,10-diphenyl-4,5,8,9-tetramethyl-5,8-diaza-2,11-dioxa-1-stanna(II)tricyclo[3.2.3.0.0]-undecane}tungsten(0)
(4). A solution of W(CO)6 (2.50 g, 7.04 mmol) in dry THF (250 mL) was
irradiated with UV light, and the volume of the carbon monoxide formed
was measured. After 150 mL of CO had been formed (within a period of 1.5
h), the UV irradiation was stopped and the reaction mixture was
evaporated under reduced pressure to a volume of 100 mL The concentrated
solution was added to a suspension of the stannylene 2 (3.33 g, 7.04
mmol) in dry THF (80 mL), and the mixture was stirred at room temperature
for 24 h. The solvent was removed under reduced pressure. Crystallization
from dichloromethane/hexane.
Pentacarbonyl{(3R,4S,9S,10R)-3,10-diphenyl-4,5,8,9-tetramethyl-5,8-diaza-2,11-dioxa-1-stanna(II)tricyclo[3.2.3.0.0]-undecane}tungsten(0)
(4). (5.46 g, 6.62 mmol, 94.0%) as yellowish amorphous solid. colorless
needles of 4, as its hexane solvate 4·0.5C6H14. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CD2Cl2):
δ 7.55-7.32 (m, 10H, Ph-H), 5.57 (d, 3J (1H-1H) = 4.5 Hz, 1H, (Ph)CH),
5.20 (d, 3J (1H-1H) = 2.5 Hz, 1H, (Ph)CH), 3.60-3.43 (m, 1H, (Me)CH),
3.35-3.22 (m, 1H, (Me)CH), 3.22-3.08 (m, 1H, NCH-H), 3.02-2.70 (m, 3H,
NCH-H), 2.90 (s, 3H, NCH3), 2.37 (s, 3H, NCH3), 1.08 (d, 3J (1H-1H) = 6.9
Hz, 3H, CH3) 1.04 (d, 3J (1H-1H) = 6.7 Hz, 3H, CH3). 13C{1H} NMR (101
MHz, CD2Cl2): δ 199.9 (s, W-CO), 198.3 (s, W-CO), 143.9 (Ph-Cipso), 143.5
(Ph-Cipso), 127.9 (Ph-C), 126.6 (Ph-C), 126.1 (Ph-C), 143.1 (Ph-C), 128.4
(Ph-C), 127.0 (Ph-C), 126.4 (Ph-C), 77.2 ((Ph)CO), 72.9 ((Ph)CO), 68.8
((Me)CH), 63.7 ((Me)CH), 54.1 (NCH2), 50.2 (NCH2), 46.6 (NCH3), 39.4
(NCH3), 10.7 (CCH3), 10.3 (CCH3). 119Sn NMR (112 MHz, CD2Cl2): δ-112 (s,
1J (119Sn-183W) = 1469 Hz). 119Sn CP-MAS NMR (149 MHz): δiso-118 (4),-722
(impurity, not defined). Mp = 199 °C (decomposition). Anal. Calcd. for
C27H30N2O7SnW (%): C 40.7, H 3.8, N 3.5. Found: C 41.1, H 3.8, N 2.9. MS
(ESI +): m/z = 860.0 [M + Na + CH3CN]+, 763.1 [2 + W(CO)3 + Na]+, 583.2
[2 + Na + CH3CN]+, 497.1 [2 + Na]+, 475.2 [2 + H]+. Crystallographic
data: empirical formula: C30H37N2O7SnW, formula weight: 797.07, crystal
system: orthorhombic, space group: P212121, unit cell dimensions: a /Å:
7.0554(4), b /Å: 16.776(2), c /Å: 25.249(6), Z: 4, crystal size/mm: 0.22
× 0.20 × 0.06.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Preparation of cis,mer-[MoCl2(NCOMe)(κ3-P4)]
(7x). To a solution of 3a.0.5(C6H6) (86 mg, 0.10 mmol) in THF (5 mL) was
added acetyl chloride (11 μL, 0.15 mmol), and the solution was stirred at
room temperature for 1 h. The color of the solution changed from
reddish-orange to green. Concentration of the solution in vacuo followed
by addition of hexane formed green crystals of 7x.THF (78 mg, 76% yield).
cis,mer-[MoCl2(NCOR)(κ3-P4)] (R = p-Tol (7z)), as yellow-green crystals,
Yield 90% 1H NMR (acetoned6): δ 2.36 (s, 3H, Me), 2.4-2.55 (m, 1H, PCH2),

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Compound IV. To a mixture of 0.61 g (0.8 mmol)
of tris(2-methoxy-5-bromophenyl)antimony benzene solvate and 0.53 g (1.6
mmol) of tribromophenol in 50 ml of diethyl ether was added 0.09 ml of
30% aqueous solution of hydrogen peroxide. The mixture was kept for 18 h
at 20 °C. The resulting crystals were filtered off and dried. Compound
XI, yield 93%. mp 181 °C.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Compound IV. To a mixture of 0.61 g (0.8 mmol) of
tris(2-methoxy-5-bromophenyl)antimony benzene solvate and 0.53 g (1.6
mmol) of tribromophenol in 50 ml of diethyl ether was added 0.09 ml of
30% aqueous solution of hydrogen peroxide. The mixture was kept for 18 h
at 20 °C. The resulting crystals were filtered off and dried. Compound
IV, yield 0.98 g, 93%. mp 164 °C. IR spectrum, ν, cm-1: 3073, 3003, 2963,
2836, 2522, 1565, 1457, 1424, 1367, 1278, 1237, 1175, 1136, 1097, 1052,
1007, 904, 858, 807, 729, 690, 613, 561. Found, %: C 29.38; 1.44.
C33H22Br9.O5Sb. Calculated, %: C 29.50; 1.64.

$DATUM [(HL)2Fe6(NCMe)4][PF6]2 (4). To a stirred suspension of 1 (0.200 g, 0.181
mmol) in MeCN (15 mL) was added a solution of [Cp2Fe](PF6) (0.120 g,
0.363 mmol) in MeCN (15 mL), giving a dark brown slurry. The slurry was
stirred for 12 h to give a dark solution. The solvent was removed under
vacuum, and the resulting solid was washed with Et2O (4 x 15 mL) to
remove Cp2Fe. The dark red residue was extracted into MeCN, filtered
through a plug of diatomaceous earth, and dried under vacuum to give
0.255 g (90%) of product. Single crystals, suitable for X-ray
diffraction, were obtained by vapor diffusion of diethyl ether into a
concentrated solution of 4 in MeCN, stored at -35 °C. 1H NMR (CD3CN, 400
MHz, δ, ppm): 15.9 (br s, N-H), 7.28 (br s, aromatic C-H), 6.32 (br s,
aromatic C-H), 5.58 (br s, aromatic C-H), 1.96 (s, NC-CH 3), 0.81 (s,
C-CH 3), -12.6 (br s, C-CH aHb-N), -13.7 (br s, C-CHa H b-N). Zero-field
57Fe Mössbauer (δ, |ΔE Q| (mm/s)): (100 K) component 1, 0.35, 2.68 (γ =
0.19 mm/s) (33%); component 2, 0.46, 2.18 (γ = 0.19 mm/s) (67%). Anal.
Calcd for C54H60F12Fe6N16P2: C, 41.62; H, 3.88; N, 14.38. Found: C,
41.48; H, 3.97; N, 14.26.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Method B. Complex 1·C6H6 (21 mg, 3 x 10-3
mmol) was added to a solution of copper
5,15-bis(diethoxyphosphoryl)-10,20-diphenylporphyrin (4Cu) (2.4 mg, 3 x
10-3 mmol) in chloroform (2 mL). The solution was heated to reflux until
complete dissolution of the copper complex, cooled, and kept at room
temperature for 1 day. A violet solid was separated by decantation under
Ar, washed with cold acetonitrile (3 x 10 mL), benzene (1 x 5 mL), and
hexane (1 x 5 mL), and dried at room temperature under Ar. The crystals
decompose at room temperature in air or under reduced pressure after
10−15 min giving a powder of 5Cu. The complex was obtained.
{Cu2(μ-OOC-t-Bu)4[μ-[O=P(OEt)2]2Por(Ph)2Ni]}n (5Ni). Prepared from 4Ni
(2.3 mg, 3 x 10-3 mmol) according to method B for 5Cu. The complex was
obtained as green-violet crystals in 93% (3.7 mg) yield. The crystals
decompose at room temperature in air or under reduced pressure after
10−15 min giving 5Ni as a violet-green powder. Calcd for
NiCu2C60H74N4O14P2: C, 54.47; H, 5.64; N, 4.02. Found: C, 54.44; H, 5.63;
N, 4.06. νmax/cm-1: 2954 m, 1615 vs, 1539 w, 1482 m, 1456 m, 1417 s, 1376
m, 1362 m, 1226 vs, 1205 w, 1163 w, 1095 w, 1063 m, 1043 m, 1013 m, 1002
m, 980 m, 890 s, 797 s, 750 s, 733 m, 700 m, 668 m, 620 m; f.w.: 1561.7;
colour: violet-green; temp (K): 150(2); crystal system: monoclinic; space
group: C 2/c; unit cell dimensions: a = 37.263(4); (Å,deg): b =
18.4352(19); : c = 12.8641(13); : α = 90; : β = 109.993(2); : γ = 90;
V(Å3): 8304.4(15); Z (Z'): 4(2); d(calculated) (Mg/m3): 1.249; abs coeff
(mm-1): 1.017; F(000): 3224; crystal size (mm): 0.16 x 0.14 x 0.12.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Supramolecular Assembly of Organophosphonate Diesters Using Paddle-Wheel
Complexes: First Examples in Porphyrin Series

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Formation of trans-[MoCl(NH)(κ4-P4)][BF4] (4a[BF4]) by Protonation of 3a
with HBF4. To a solution of 3a (301 mg, 0.35 mmol) in benzene (25 mL) was
added 54% HBF4 in diethyl ether (58 μL, 0.42 mmol) at room temperature
with stirring. After 70 min, the deposited pink solid of
4a[BF4].0.25(C6H6) was filtered off, washed successively with benzene (15
mL) and diethyl ether (15 mL), and then dried under vacuum (309 mg, 91%
yield). trans-[MoCl(NH)(κ4-P4)][BF4] (4a[BF4]), Yield (309 mg, 91%). 1H
NMR (CD2Cl2): δ 2.85-3.10 (m, 6H, PCH2), 3.25-3.45 (m, 2H, PCH2), 4.62
(br, 1H, NH), 7.00-7.35 (m, 20H, aromatic H), 7.5- 7.6 (m, 6H, aromatic
H), 7.75-7.80 (m, 2H, aromatic H), 7.90- 8.05 (m, 6H, aromatic H), 7.35
(s, 1.5H, 0.25C6H6). 13C{1H} NMR (CD2Cl2): δ 56.8, 92.3 (AA'XX' pattern:
JAX = 5, JAX' = 129, JAA' ) 22, JXX' = 9 Hz). IR (KBr, cm-1): 3203 (ν
(N-H)). Anal. Calcd for C47.5H44.5BClF4MoNP4: C, 58.73; H, 4.62; N, 1.44.
Found: C, 58.83; H, 4.63; N, 1.39. Single crystals for X-ray analysis
were obtained by recrystallization from CH2Cl2/Et2O as purple crystals of
4a[BF4].0.25(CH2Cl2)δ 0.25(Et2O). Anal. Calcd for

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 3.4. Synthesis of Zirconasilacyclopentanes 5
and 6. Zirconocene dichloride (1.3 equiv) and the dipotassium silyl
compound were dissolved in toluene. The deep red solution was stirred at
room temperature for 6 h. The solvent was removed in a vacuum, and the
residue dissolved in pentane. The resulting solution was filtered and
cooled to -30°C to obtain the crystalline product.
1,1-Dicyclopentadienyl-3,3,4,4-tetramethyl-2,2,5,5-tetrakis(trimethylsilyl)-1-zirconacyclopentasilane
(6). Using dianion 2a deep red crystals16 of 6 were obtained in 90%
yield. Mp: 167-170°C (dec). 1H NMR (C6D6, δ ppm): 6.29 (s, 10 H, Cp);
0.45 (s, 12 H, SiMe2); 0.43 (s, 36 H, SiMe3). 13C NMR (C6D6,δ ppm): 108.8
(Cp); 6.9 (SiMe3); 2.2 (SiMe2). 29Si NMR (pentane, D2O, δ ppm): -2.4
(SiMe3); -29.2 (SiMe3); -65.2 (SiZr). Anal. Calcd for C26H58Si8Zr: C
45.48; H 8.51. Found: C 45.01, H 8.47.

$DATUM Synthesis of [P14,6,6,6]2[Co(DBCat)(DBSQ)(DCOObpy)]. Equimolar amounts of
[P14,6,6,6]2[DCOObpy] (0.59 g, 0.49 mmol) and [Co(DBSQ)2]4·2PhH (0.26 g,
0.49 mmol)2 were dissolved in anhydrous ethanol (75 cm3) in inert
atmosphere (H2O, O2 &lt; 1 ppm). After being stirring overnight, the
green solution was evaporated under vacuum at room temperature to give
dark green viscous liquid (0.79 g, 0.46 mmol, 94% yield). Tg= -11 °C, Td
~ 80 °C. No trace of Na, Ag, and Cl was detected for EDS, and no signal
ascribable to ethanol solvent was detected for 1H NMR. IR (KBr) νmax:
2956m, 2926s, 2856s, 1618s, 1553m, 1463s, 1375s, 1286m, 1243m, 1206w,
1096w, 1067w, 1028w, 985m, 906w, 852w, 827w, 788m, 724w, 704m, 652w,
573w, 521w, 495w, 437w cm-1.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for stoichiometric reactions
of 2a: Complex 2a (20.0 mg, 0.0169 mmol) and Si2Me6 (1.0 μL) were
dissolved in 0.4 mL of THF-d8. A 1H-NMR spectrum was acquired. To this
solution was added the combination of a primary or secondary amine and
triethylamine, an alkali metal alkoxide, sodium 2-methylpentanoate, or an
alkali metal malonate as nucleophile. Reactions of the primary amines
were conducted with 5.0 equiv of the primary amine and 1.2 equiv of the
tertiary amine; the other reactions were conducted with 1.2 equiv of the
nucleophile. The resulting mixture was stirred for 5 min. A solution of
PPh3 (4.9 mg, 0.019 mmol) in 0.1 mL of THF-d8 was then added, at which
point the solution turned yellow. A second 1H-NMR spectrum was acquired,
and the yields of the organic product were determined by integration of
the two 1H-NMR spectra vs the Si2Me6 internal standard. The identity of
the allylation products was confirmed by comparing the GC retention times
with commercially available material or independently synthesized
products. Yield 100%

$DATUM Synthesis of
[1,4-bis(2-(diisopropylphosphino)phenyl)-2,3-quinone]dicarbonylmolybdenum(0)
(3) A solution of 2a (0.0215 g, 0.0319 mmol) in THF (0.6 mL) was added to
a J. Young style NMR tube and degassed via three freeze-pump-thaw cycles.
An atmosphere of O2 was then added to the headspace and the tube inverted
for 60 seconds. 31P NMR spectroscopy revealed complete conversion to a
new species at approximately 72 ppm. The volatiles were removed under
vacuum, and the residue was dissolved in MeCN (2 mL) and then the
volatiles removed under vacuum, repeating this multiple times to remove
the H2O side product. Finally, the residue was triturated with Hexanes
and the volatiles removed under vacuum. The desired product in 96.4%
yield (0.0198 g, 0.0307 mmol). Refluxing the compound in PhMe for an hour
and then allowing the solution to cool to room temperature formed
crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CD3CN , 25 °C),
δ(ppm): 7.43-7.68 (m, 8 H, Ar-CH), 5.09 (s, 2 H, C1H), 3.11 (m, 2 H,
PCH(CH3)2). 2.93 (m, 2 H, PCH(CH3)2), 1.10-1.34 (m, 18 H, PCH(CH3)2),
0.82-0.92 (m, 6 H, PCH(CH3)2). 31P NMR (121 MHz, CD3CN , 25 °C), δ(ppm):
72.43 (s). 13C NMR (126 MHz, CD3CN , 25 °C), δ(ppm): 246.34 (t, 20 Hz,
Mo-CO), 222.58 (t, 18 Hz, Mo-CO), 173.31 (s, quinonoid Ar-CO), 138.02
(m), 135.81 (m), 134.51 (s), 134.12 (s), 132.62 (t), 132.10 (t), 130.02
(t), 100.58 (s, quinonoid Ar-CH), 65.30 (s, OCH3), 29.58 (m, PCH(CH3)2),
28.98 (s, PCH(CH3)2), 19.03 (s, PCH(CH3)2), 18.30 (t, PCH(CH3)2), 18.12
(s, PCH(CH3)2), 18.04 (s, PCH(CH3)2). IR (THF), ν CO (cm-1): 1875, 1605.
Anal. Calcd for [3], C32H38MoO4P2: C, 59.63; H, 5.94. Found: C, 60.11; H,
6.04.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for stoichiometric reactions
of 2a: Complex 2a (20.0 mg, 0.0169 mmol) and Si2Me6 (1.0 μL) were
dissolved in 0.4 mL of THF-d8. A 1H-NMR spectrum was acquired. To this
solution was added the combination of a primary or secondary amine and
triethylamine, an alkali metal alkoxide, sodium 2-methylpentanoate, or an
alkali metal malonate as nucleophile. Reactions of the primary amines
were conducted with 5.0 equiv of the primary amine and 1.2 equiv of the
tertiary amine; the other reactions were conducted with 1.2 equiv of the
nucleophile. The resulting mixture was stirred for 5 min. A solution of
PPh3 (4.9 mg, 0.019 mmol) in 0.1 mL of THF-d8 was then added, at which
point the solution turned yellow. A second 1H-NMR spectrum was acquired,
and the yields of the organic product were determined by integration of
the two 1H-NMR spectra vs the Si2Me6 internal standard. The identity of
the allylation products was confirmed by comparing the GC retention times
with commercially available material or independently synthesized
products. Dimethyl 2-(but-3-en-2-yl)malonate The reaction was conducted
according to the general procedure. The crude product was passed through
a fritted glass filter packed with Celite layered on silica gel and
eluted with 20 ml of EtOAc. The solvents were removed under reduced
pressure, and the product was purified by silica gel chromatography,
eluting with 9:1 (hexane:EtOAc). 1H NMR (499 MHz, CDCl3) δ 5.77 (ddd, J=
8.0, 10.3, 17.2, 1H), 5.09 (d, J= 17.1, 1H), 5.01 (d, J= 10.3, 1H), 3.74
(s, 3H), 3.70 (s, 3H), 3.32 (d, J= 8.9, 1H), 2.95 (m, 1H), 1.10 (d, J=
6.8, 3H). 13C NMR (126 MHz, CDCl3) δ 168.42, 168.36, 139.49, 115.24,
57.28, 52.10, 52.00, 37.89, 17.67. The enantiomeric excess was determined
by GC: Chiraldex γ-CDTA 30 m column, 50-100 °C, 1 °/min, 90 kPa H2, tR =
37.3 (minor) min, tR = 37.6 (major) min. [α]21 D = -18.8 (c 1.25, CHCl3),
(S)-(-) Dimethyl 2-(but-3-en-2-yl)malonate.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Synthesis of FeCl Corroles 8. Method
2. A solution of 4 (0.15 mmol) and FeCl2 (380 mg, 3.00 mmol) in 20 mL of
dimethylformamide (DMF) was degassed with argon for 20 min. Subsequent
heating to reflux (110-120 °C) for 4 h resulted in a color change from
dark green to dark red. This reaction can also be conducted in amicrowave
on a solution of 3mLof DMF for 45 min at 120 °C. DMF was removed under
vacuum, and the resulting product was dissolved in 30 mL of DCM. This
solution was washed with water and brine to remove residual DMF, dried
over Na2SO4, and concentrated to dryness. The resulting crude product was
chromatographed (silica, diethylether) to afford the corresponding
hangman μ-oxo dimer as a major brown band. The collected fraction was
concentrated to dryness, and DCM(30mL) and 7% HCl(aq) (10 mL) were added.
The mixture was stirred vigorously for several hours. The organic phase
was washed with water and brine, and dried over Na2SO4. The resulting
solution was concentrated to dryness, and the resulting product was
suspended in methanol, filtered, and dried in vacuum.
10-(4-(5-Bromo-2,7-di-tert-butyl-9,9-dimethylxanthenyl))-5,
15-bis(tert-butylphenyl)corrolato Iron-μ-oxo Dimer (7a). Dimer 7a was
obtained by stirring a solution of 8a in dichloromethane vigorously
overnight with a 0.1 M aqueous solution of NaOH. Subsequent extraction
with water and brine, followed by drying the organic phase over NaSO4 and
removal of solvent to dryness. 7a in almost quantitative yield.
HR(ESI)-MS (MH+) (M=C124H124N8O3Br2Fe2): Calcd for m/z = 2046.6964, found
2046.6960. MS(MALDI/TOF) (MH)+: 2046.35.UV-vis, nm (ε × 10-3M-1 cm-1):
388 (105), 518 (19) in DCM.

Thomas S.; Nocera, Daniel G.
